based on|[[Hua Mulan|''Ballad of Mulan'']]|[[Guo Maoqian]]}}\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Liu Yifei]]\n* [[Donnie Yen]]\n* [[Jason Scott Lee]]\n* [[Yoson An]]\n* [[Gong Li]]\n* [[Jet Li]] \n}}\n| music          = [[Harry Gregson-Williams]]<ref name=\"Gregson-Williams\">{{Cite web |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/08/22/harry-gregson-williams-to-score-disneys-mulan-live-action-movie/ |title=Harry-Gregson-Williams to Score Disney's 'Mulan' Live-Action Movie |website=Film Music Reporter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824135101/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2018/08/22/harry-gregson-williams-to-score-disneys-mulan-live-action-movie/ |archive-date=August 24, 2018 |access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n| cinematography = [[Mandy Walker]]\n| editing        = David Coulson\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n* Jason T. Reed Productions\n* Good Fear\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2020|3|9|[[Hollywood]]|2020|7|24|United States}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $200  million<ref name=CNNbudget>{{Cite news |url= https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2020/02/13/media/disney-mulan-coronavirus/index.html |title= Disney's 'Mulan' was supposed to be a big hit in China. The coronavirus could threaten that |last= Pallotta |first=Frank |date=February 14, 2020 |work=[[CNN Business]]|access-date=February 22, 2020}}</ref> \n| gross          = N/A<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt4566758/?ref_=bo_rl_ti | title=Mulan (2020) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Mulan''''' is a 2020 American [[action drama]] film directed by [[Niki Caro]], with the screenplay by [[Rick Jaffa and Amanda Silver|Rick Jaffa, Amanda Silver]], Lauren Hynek, and Elizabeth Martin, and produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The film is based on the Chinese folklore \"The Ballad of [[Hua Mulan|Mulan]]\" and is a [[List of Disney live-action remakes of animated films|live-action adaptation]] of [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Disney]]'s [[Mulan (1998 film)|1998 animated film of the same name]]. The film stars [[Liu Yifei]] in the [[Mulan (Disney character)|title role]], alongside [[Donnie Yen]], [[Jason Scott Lee]], [[Yoson An]], [[Gong Li]], and [[Jet Li]] in supporting roles.\n\nPlans for a live-action ''Mulan'' remake began in 2010, but the project never came to fruition. In March 2015, a new attempt was announced and Caro was hired to direct in February 2017. Liu was cast in the title role in November 2017, following a casting call of 1,000 actresses, and the rest of the cast joined over the following year. Filming began in August 2018 and lasted through November, taking place in [[New Zealand]] and [[China]].\n\n''Mulan'' is the first live-action remake from Disney to be given a PG-13 rating by the [[Motion Picture Association|MPAA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/mulan-rating-pg-13-violence-disney-1203508059/|title=\u2018Mulan\u2019 Is Disney\u2019s First Live-Action Remake to Get a PG-13 Rating|last=Rico|first=Klaritza|date=2020-02-19|website=Variety|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> It was scheduled to be released in the United States on March 27, 2020, but was delayed to July 24, 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n\n==Premise==\n{{Quote|When the Emperor of China issues a decree that one man per family must serve in the Imperial Army to defend the country from Northern invaders, Hua Mulan, the eldest daughter of an honored warrior, steps in to take the place of her ailing father. Masquerading as a man, Hua Jun, she is tested every step of the way and must harness her inner-strength and embrace her true potential. It is an epic journey that will transform her into an honored warrior and earn her the respect of a grateful nation\u2026and a proud father.|source=[[Walt Disney Pictures]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.disney.com/mulan-2020|title=Mulan (2020)|publisher=Disney Movies}}</ref>}}\n\n==Plot==\nThe original movie's plot will mostly be unchanged in the remake, with some exceptions. For example, the song \"I'll Make a Man Out of You\" was removed. Also, Mulan's original love interest, Captain Li Shang, was removed, with his role being spilt into two different characters, <ref>{{cite web|https://collider.com/mulan-changes-live-action-animated-version-disney/</ref>}}Commander Tung (Donnie Yen) and Chen Honghui (Yoson An). Also, Mushu, played by Eddie Murphy, was removed from the remake and a new character, Mulan's sister Hua Xiu, will be added. Finally, Shan Yu, the main antagonist of the original film, will not be in the remake. Instead, the main antagonist will be Xianniang, a shapeshifting witch who is an ally of Bori Khan.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Liu Yifei]] as [[Mulan (Disney character)|Mulan]], the eldest daughter of Hua Zhou who defies both tradition and the law by disguising herself as a man by the name of Hua Jun in order to enlist herself in the Imperial Army in place of her ailing father.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-42177082 |title=Mulan: Disney casts Chinese actress Liu Yifei in lead role |date=November 30, 2017 |publisher=[[BBC]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814004705/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-42177082 |archive-date=August 14, 2018 |access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n** Crystal Rao portrays a young Mulan.\n* [[Donnie Yen]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Commander Tung|Commander Tung]], the high ranking leader of the Imperial Army and mentor to Mulan.<ref name=\"Deadline1\">{{Cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/donnie-yen-mulan-disney-live-action-film-1202362542/ |title=Donnie Yen To Star In Disney's Live Action 'Mulan' |last=Fleming, Jr. |first=Mike |date=April 11, 2018 |work=Deadline |access-date=April 12, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412082921/http://deadline.com/2018/04/donnie-yen-mulan-disney-live-action-film-1202362542/ |archive-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> Both Tung and Chen are based on Li Shang from the animated film.<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\" />\n* [[Jason Scott Lee]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Shan Yu|Bori Khan]], a [[Rouran Khaganate|Rouran]]<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\" /> warrior leader intent on avenging his father's death. Khan is based on Shan Yu from the animated film.<ref name=\"HollywoodReporter1\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-mulan-adds-jason-scott-lee-1129918 |title=Disney's 'Mulan' Adds Jason Scott Lee |date=July 25, 2018 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726010208/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-mulan-adds-jason-scott-lee-1129918 |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |access-date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Yoson An]]<ref name=HollywoodReporter1/> as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Li Shang|Chen Honghui]], a confident and ambitious recruit who joins Commander Tung's unit, and becomes Mulan's ally and love interest.<ref name=\"HollywoodReporter2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mulan-disney-casts-yoson-an-as-love-interest-live-action-movie-1116949 |title=Disney Casts 'Mulan' Love Interest (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=June 6, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606230631/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mulan-disney-casts-yoson-an-as-love-interest-live-action-movie-1116949 |archive-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> Both Chen and Tung are based on Li Shang from the animated film.<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\" />\n*[[Gong Li]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Hayabusa|Xianniang]],<ref name=HollywoodReporter1/> a powerful [[Witchcraft|witch]] with [[shapeshifting]] abilities and an ally of Bori Khan.<ref name=\"HollywoodReporter3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-live-action-mulan-lands-gong-li-jet-li-1101994 |title=Disney's Live-Action 'Mulan' Lands Gong Li, Jet Li (Exclusive) |last=Sun |first=Rebecca |date=April 12, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=April 14, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413131542/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-live-action-mulan-lands-gong-li-jet-li-1101994 |archive-date=April 13, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Jet Li]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#The Emperor of China|The Emperor]] of China, a wise benevolent ruler of China who orders the mobilization of troops via the conscription of one man from each household to fight the Hun army.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/07/07/there-are-no-talking-dragons-or-singing-generals-in-this-live-action-mulan-trailer/#1f5fae1f5f0f |title=There Are No Talking Dragons Or Singing Generals In This Live-Action 'Mulan' Trailer |last=Kain, Erik |date=July 7, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713050758/https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2019/07/07/there-are-no-talking-dragons-or-singing-generals-in-this-live-action-mulan-trailer/#1f5fae1f5f0f |archive-date=July 13, 2019 |access-date=July 13, 2019 |magazine=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n* [[Tzi Ma]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Fa Zhou|Hua Zhou]], Mulan's father and a famed [[Veteran|war veteran]], who is now recalled to the Imperial Army despite his frail health.<ref name=\"HuffPost\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ming-na-wen-voice-of-animated-mulan-responds-to-new-teaser_n_5d267d35e4b0583e482badeb |title=Ming-Na Wen, Voice Of Animated Mulan, Responds To New Teaser |last=Yam, Kimberly |date=July 10, 2019 |publisher=[[HuffPost]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713090948/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ming-na-wen-voice-of-animated-mulan-responds-to-new-teaser_n_5d267d35e4b0583e482badeb |archive-date=July 13, 2019 |access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Rosalind Chao]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Fa Li|Hua Li]], Mulan's mother and Zhou's wife.<ref name=HuffPost/>\n* Xana Tang as Hua Xiu, Mulan's younger sister.<ref name=HollywoodReporter3/> The character was added to the film's plot because the filmmakers felt that \"this added a broader emotional context and added more motivation for [Mulan's] character\".<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\"/>\n* [[Ron Yuan]] as Sergeant Qiang, the fiercely loyal second in command of the Imperial Regiment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/mulan-utkarsh-ambudkar-ron-yuan-disney-1202396832/ |title='Mulan': Utkarsh Ambudkar & Ron Yuan Added To Disney's Live-Action Adaptation |last=N'Duka, Amanda |date=May 23, 2018 |publisher=Deadline |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711104710/https://deadline.com/2018/05/mulan-utkarsh-ambudkar-ron-yuan-disney-1202396832/ |archive-date=July 11, 2019 |access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Jimmy Wong]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Ling|Ling]], a recruit who joins Commander Tung's unit.<ref name=\"Deadline4\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/disney-mulan-jimmy-wong-doua-moua-1202445269/ |title=Disney's 'Mulan' Casts Jimmy Wong & Doua Moua |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=August 14, 2018 |publisher=Deadline |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814232736/https://deadline.com/2018/08/disney-mulan-jimmy-wong-doua-moua-1202445269/ |archive-date=August 14, 2018 |access-date=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Doua Moua]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Chien-Po|Chien-Po]], a recruit who joins Commander Tung's unit.<ref name=Deadline4/>\n* [[Chen Tang (actor)|Chen Tang]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Yao|Yao]], a recruit who joins Commander Tung's unit.<ref name=\"Deadline5\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/adrian-martinez-disney-lady-and-the-tramp-mulan-chen-tang-1202469095/ |title=Adrian Martinez Joins Disney's 'Lady and the Tramp'; 'Mulan' Adds Chen Tang |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=September 21, 2018 |publisher=Deadline |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921230311/https://deadline.com/2018/09/adrian-martinez-disney-lady-and-the-tramp-mulan-chen-tang-1202469095/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |access-date=September 21, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson Lee]] as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Chi-Fu|The Chancellor]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://movieweb.com/mulan-2020-disney-remake-trailer-release-date/ |title=Disney's Mulan Remake Trailer Drops This Sunday |last=Sprague, Mike |date=July 6, 2019 |publisher=MovieWeb |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708141758/https://movieweb.com/mulan-2020-disney-remake-trailer-release-date/ |archive-date=July 8, 2019 |access-date=July 13, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Cheng Pei-pei]]<ref name=Deadline3/> as [[List of Disney's Mulan characters|The Matchmaker]] \n* [[Utkarsh Ambudkar]] as Skatch, a con artist and friend of Ramtish.<ref name=HollywoodReporter2/>\n* Chum Ehelepola as Ramtish, a con artist and friend of Skatch.<ref name=HollywoodReporter2/>\n* Arka Das as Red Fez\n* Jun Yu as Cricket, an archer.<ref name=\"Liptak\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/7/20685171/mulan-live-action-yifei-liu-niki-caro-animation-remake-first-trailer-watch |title=Watch the first trailer for Disney's live-action remake of Mulan |last=Liptak |first=Andrew |date=July 7, 2019 |website=[[The Verge]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707165408/https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/7/20685171/mulan-live-action-yifei-liu-niki-caro-animation-remake-first-trailer-watch |archive-date=July 7, 2019 |access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"MulanOnSet\">{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/mulan-changes-live-action-animated-version-disney/|title=\u2018Mulan\u2019: The Biggest Changes from the Animated Version in Disney\u2019s Live-Action Remake|website=Collider|last=Szany|first=Wendy Lee|date=February 27, 2020|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[Walt Disney Pictures]] expressed interest in a [[List of Disney live-action remakes of animated films|live-action adaptation]] of the 1998 animated film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' starring international star [[Zhang Ziyi]], with [[Chuck Russell]] chosen as the director. The film was originally planned to start filming in October 2010, but was canceled.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/entertainment/view/1071985/1/.html |title=Zhang Ziyi to produce and star in 3D Mulan film |date=July 28, 2010 |website=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318082003/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/entertainment/view/1071985/1/.html |archive-date=March 18, 2013}}</ref> On March 30, 2015, ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' reported that Disney had restarted development of the live-action adaptation with [[Chris Bender (film producer)|Chris Bender]] and [[J. C. Spink]] producing, while Elizabeth Martin and Lauren Hynek would be writing the screenplay.<ref name=\"DevelopingMulan\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-developing-live-action-mulan-784892/ |title=Disney Developing Live-Action 'Mulan' (Exclusive) |last=Ford |first=Rebecca |date=March 30, 2015 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403121534/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disney-developing-live-action-mulan-784892 |archive-date=April 3, 2015 |access-date=April 5, 2015}}</ref> On October 4, 2016, it was announced that [[Rick Jaffa and Amanda Silver]] would rewrite the script, combining the Chinese ballad and the 1998 animated film, while Jason T. Reed would be producing the film along with [[Chris Bender (film producer)|Chris Bender]] and Jake Weiner.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/mulan-release-date-live-action-disney-1201877832/ |title=Disney's Live-Action 'Mulan' to Hit Theaters in November 2018; Rick Jaffa and Amanda Silver Rewriting |last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=October 4, 2016 |work=Variety |access-date=October 5, 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005192448/http://variety.com/2016/film/news/mulan-release-date-live-action-disney-1201877832/ |archive-date=October 5, 2016}}</ref> In February 27, 2020, Reed revealed that Mulan's sidekick from the original film, [[Mushu]], was removed due to the character's negative reception in China.<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\"/> Redd also said, aside from both the original ballad and the animated film, the filmmakers drew inspiration from different Chinese adaptations of the ballad while writing the film, stating that, since \"[t]he traditional Disney audience and the diaspora Asian audience viewed the movie in one way, and the traditional Chinese in China audience viewed a slightly different way\", the filmmakers \"dug in to try and make sure that [they are] addressing both of those audiences in a thoughtful way\".<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\"/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Liu Yifei at the 2016 BAZAAR Stars\u2019 Charity Night.jpg|thumb|upright|Liu Yifei plays Mulan in the remake.]]\nSince several recent Hollywood films were accused of [[Whitewashing in film|whitewashing]], ''Mulan'' has been under intense scrutiny since ''The Hollywood Reporter'' reported that Disney was making a live-action adaptation of ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]''. An [[online petition]] titled \"Tell Disney You Don't Want A Whitewashed Mulan!\" received more than 100,000 signatures.<ref name=BBC/> On October 4, 2016, Disney announced that a global search for a Chinese actress to portray the title role was underway.<ref name=\"FindingMulan\">{{Cite news|last=McClintock |first=Pamela |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disneys-live-action-mulan-gets-934976 |title=Disney's Live-Action 'Mulan' Gets Winter 2018 Release Date |date=October 4, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618014152/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/disneys-live-action-mulan-gets-934976 |archive-date=June 18, 2018 |access-date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> A team of casting directors visited five continents and saw nearly 1,000 candidates for the role with criteria that required credible martial arts skills, the ability to speak clear English, and star quality.<ref name=\"YifeiCast\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-mulan-finds-star-1061585 |title=Disney's 'Mulan' Finds Its Star (Exclusive) |last=Sun |first=Rebecca |date=November 29, 2017 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=January 17, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044128/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-mulan-finds-star-1061585?utm_source=twitter |archive-date=December 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 29, 2017, Chinese-American actress [[Liu Yifei]] was cast in the film to portray the titular role of Mulan. Many celebrated this as a win for diversity in Disney films.<ref name=BBC/> Further cast announcements for [[Donnie Yen]], [[Gong Li]], [[Jet Li]], and Xana Tang were made in April 2018,<ref name=Deadline1/><ref name=HollywoodReporter3/> [[Utkarsh Ambudkar]] and [[Ron Yuan]] in May,<ref name=\"AmbudkarYuanCast\">{{Cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/mulan-utkarsh-ambudkar-ron-yuan-disney-1202396832/ |title='Mulan': Utkarsh Ambudkar & Ron Yuan Added To Disney's Live-Action Adaptation |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=May 23, 2018 |work=Deadline |access-date=May 24, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524151432/http://deadline.com/2018/05/mulan-utkarsh-ambudkar-ron-yuan-disney-1202396832/ |archive-date=May 24, 2018}}</ref> [[Yoson An]] and Chum Ehelepola in June,<ref name=HollywoodReporter2/> [[Jason Scott Lee]] in July,<ref name=HollywoodReporter1/> [[Tzi Ma]], [[Rosalind Chao]], [[Cheng Pei-Pei]], [[Nelson Lee]], [[Jimmy Wong]] and [[Doua Moua]] in August,<ref name=\"Deadline3\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/mulan-production-starting-new-cast-disney-1202444587/ |title='Mulan' Rounds Out Cast, Reveals First-Look Photo As Filming Underway On Live-Action Movie |last=Hipes |first=Patrick |date=August 13, 2018 |publisher=Deadline |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813184830/https://deadline.com/2018/08/mulan-production-starting-new-cast-disney-1202444587/ |archive-date=August 13, 2018 |access-date=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Deadline4\"/> and [[Chen Tang (actor)|Chen Tang]] in September.<ref name=Deadline5/>\n\n===Director===\nDisney originally sought an Asian director. Disney first considered [[Ang Lee]], Taiwanese film director and two-time [[Academy Award]] winner for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]. ''The Hollywood Reporter'' mentioned that Lee was approached but declined on October 12, 2016.<ref name=\"LeePass\">{{Cite news|last=Ford|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mulan-mania-disney-sony-hunt-937274 |title='Mulan' Mania: Disney, Sony Hunt for Asian Directors to Helm Rival Action Pics |date=October 12, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814001804/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/mulan-mania-disney-sony-hunt-937274 |archive-date=August 14, 2018 |access-date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> According to the report, published on November 22, 2016, he said that he would like to see an Asian director leading the film, but he himself had to decline because he was still obliged to promote his film ''[[Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk (film)|Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk]]''.<ref name=\"LeeSaid\">{{Cite news |last=Lee |first=Ashley |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/ang-lee-disneys-live-action-mulan-itd-be-great-see-an-asian-director-949162 |title=Ang Lee on Disney's Live-Action 'Mulan': \"It'd Be Great to See an Asian\" Director |date=November 22, 2016 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180814001739/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/ang-lee-disneys-live-action-mulan-itd-be-great-see-an-asian-director-949162 |archive-date=August 14, 2018 |access-date=June 22, 2018}}</ref> Next, Disney met with [[Jiang Wen]] for the position; finally on February 14, 2017, [[Niki Caro]] was hired as the director of the film, which made ''Mulan'' the second Disney film with a female director and a budget above $100 million following ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]''.<ref name=\"NikiHelm\">{{Cite news |last=Sun |first=Rebecca |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-live-action-mulan-finds-director-975869 |title=Disney's Live-Action 'Mulan' Finds Director (Exclusive) |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=February 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216072040/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/disneys-live-action-mulan-finds-director-975869 |archive-date=February 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] began on August 13, 2018, at different locations in New Zealand and China and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on November 25, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://omegaunderground.com/2018/04/12/update-disney-to-begin-shooting-mulan-this-august-in-new-zealand-and-china/ |title=UPDATE: Disney To Begin Shooting 'Mulan' This August In New Zealand and China - Omega Underground |last=Marc |first=Christopher |date=April 12, 2018 |work=omegaunderground.com |access-date=April 12, 2018 |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816062124/https://thegww.com/update-disney-to-begin-shooting-mulan-this-august-in-new-zealand-and-china/}}</ref><ref name=Deadline3/> According to actress [[Gong Li]], the film's production budget was $290\u2013300 million due to the \"massive and...unprecedented scale\" of the sets,<ref name=\"GongLiBudget\">{{Cite web |url=https://heroichollywood.com/mulan-disney-li-gong-budget/ |title=Gong Li Claims Live-Action 'Mulan' Budget Is More Than $300 Million |last=Caesar Galvin |date=May 19, 2019 |website=Heroic Hollywood |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718220408/https://heroichollywood.com/mulan-disney-li-gong-budget/ |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"GongLiBudget2\">{{Cite web |last=Bonomolo |first=Cameron |url=https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/05/07/disney-live-action-mulan-budget-most-expensive-movies-ever-made/ |title=Disney's Live-Action 'Mulan' Budget Makes It One of the Most Expensive Movies Ever Made |date=May 8, 2019 |website=ComicBook.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718183231/https://comicbook.com/movies/2018/05/07/disney-live-action-mulan-budget-most-expensive-movies-ever-made/ |archive-date=July 18, 2019 |access-date=July 19, 2019}}</ref> although the actual figure was later reported to be $200 million.<ref name=CNNbudget/><ref>{{cite news|last=Ford|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/inside-disneys-bold-200m-gamble-mulan-stakes-couldnt-be-higher-1280999|title=Inside Disney's Bold $200M Gamble on 'Mulan': \"The Stakes Couldn't Be Higher\"|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Post-production===\nThe visual effects are provided by [[Sony Pictures Imageworks]], [[Weta Digital]], [[Framestore]], and [[Image Engine]], with Seth Maury and [[Anders Langlands|Andres Langlands]] serving as visual effects supervisors and [[Sean Andrew Faden]] serving as production supervisor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.artofvfx.com/mulan/ |title=Mulan - ART OF VFX |date=July 8, 2019 |website=www.artofvfx.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708122921/https://www.artofvfx.com/mulan/ |archive-date=July 8, 2019 |access-date=July 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nDirector [[Niki Caro]] revealed that the remake won't feature any songs from the original film;<ref>{{Cite web |last=Taylor |first=Drew |url=https://www.moviefone.com/2017/03/17/mulan-exclusive-niki-caro/ |title=Exclusive: 'Mulan' Director Niki Caro Says No Songs in the Upcoming Remake |date=March 17, 2018 |website=MovieFone |url-status=live |access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> the film instead will feature instrumental versions of the original film's songs.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Colon |first=Jessenika |url=https://thedisinsider.com/2019/06/29/exclusive-phoenix-possibly-replacing-mushu-in-mulan-cast-will-not-sing-classic-songs/ |title=EXCLUSIVE: Phoenix Possibly Replacing Mushu in 'Mulan'; Cast Will Not Sing Classic Songs |date=June 30, 2019|website=www.thedisinsider.com |url-status=live |access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Caro later explained that the songs were deleted because she felt it didn't fit with her realistic vision of the film, she believes that since people do not break out into song as they enter war, the film should not either. Though she still tried to \"honour the music from the animation in a very significant way\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/benhenry/mulan-director-niki-caro-q-and-a|title=The Director Of \"Mulan\" Just Revealed Why There Won't Be Any Songs In Disney's Live-Action Remake|date=January 13, 2020|website=BuzzFeed|url-status=live|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>, she did not want to disrespect the original film in anyway; however, she claimed she could not find a place to squeeze in the original music. Producer Jason T. Reed clarified Caro's previous statement by saying that the songs will be featured \"in a slightly different way\" in the remake.<ref name=\"MulanOnSet\"/>\n\n[[Harry Gregson-Williams]], who previously worked with Caro on ''[[The Zookeeper's Wife (film)|The Zookeeper's Wife]]'', composed the film's score.<ref name=\"Gregson-Williams\"/>\n\n[[Matthew Wilder]], who previously co-wrote the songs for the original film, revealed that the remake will feature a new version of the song \"[[Reflection (song)|Reflection]]\", and that the song \"thematically plays a large part in the new movie throughout the score\".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shuler |first=Skyler |url=https://thedisinsider.com/2020/02/13/matthew-wilder-reflection-mulan/ |title=Songwriter Matthew Wilder Discusses \"Reflection\" In Disney\u2019s \u2018Mulan\u2019 |date=February 13, 2020|website=www.thedisinsider.com |url-status=live |access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> [[Christina Aguilera]], who previously performed an end-credits version of \"Reflection\" for the original film, confirmed during a performance in [[The Xperience]] that she had recorded a new version of \"Reflection\", as well as new material for the remake's soundtrack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lenker |first=Maureen Lee |url=https://ew.com/movies/christina-aguilera-new-mulan-music/ |title=Original 'Reflection' singer Christina Aguilera has recorded new material for live-action Mulan |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=February 27, 2020 |accessdate=March 4, 2020}}</ref> On March 6, 2020, she released a new single for the film's soundtrack, titled \"Loyal Brave True\". The song was written by Jamie Hartman, Harry Gregson-Williams, Rosi Golan and Billy Crabtree, and produced by Jamie Hartman. The song was also released in Spanish, as \u201cEl Mejor Guerrero.\u201d Additionally, the singer confirmed that she would also release a re-recorded version of \"Reflection\".\n<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedigitalfix.com/music/new-music/christina-aguilera-shares-her-track-loyal-brave-true-taken-from-the-upcoming-disney-remake-of-mulan/ |title=Christina Aguilera shares her track, 'Loyal Brave True', taken from the upcoming Disney remake of Mulan|website=The Digital Fix |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news|first=Joey|last=Nolfi|url=https://ew.com/movies/christina-aguilera-new-song-loyal-brave-true-mulan/|title=Hear Christina Aguilera's warrior spirit on new Mulan ballad 'Loyal Brave True'|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 6, 2020}}</ref> On March 8, a [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]-version of the song performed by Liu Yifei was released.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202003/09/WS5e65cb3ca31012821727d709.html|title=Chinese version of 'Reflection' released for upcoming 'Mulan' - Chinadaily.com.cn|last=\u987e\u99a8|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> Liu's interpretation is a revisitation of the Mandarin-language version of Aguilera's song, originally performed for the animated movie by [[Hong Kong]]-[[Chinese Americans|Chinese American]] singer [[Coco Lee]], who also voiced Mulan in the [[Taiwanese Mandarin]] dubbing in 1998.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f7Z6FhaAPFI|title=\u674e\u739f CoCo Lee - \u81ea\u5df1|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://disneyinternationalvoices.weebly.com/mulan.html|title=Mulan|website=CHARGUIGOU|language=fr|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\nOn July 7, 2019, the official teaser trailer and the official teaser poster were released during the broadcast of the [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup Final]].<ref name=\"Liptak\"/> The teaser trailer was viewed 175.1 million times in its first 24 hours, including 52 million from China, making it [[List of most-viewed online videos in the first 24 hours#Top trailers|the seventh most viewed trailer in that time period]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/mulan-teaser-trailer-175-million-views-24-hours-china-worldwide-disney-1202643480/ |title='Mulan' Teaser Trailer Logs Epic 175M+ Views In First 24 Hours, Including 52M From China |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=July 9, 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190827031552/https://deadline.com/2019/07/mulan-teaser-trailer-175-million-views-24-hours-china-worldwide-disney-1202643480/ |archive-date=August 27, 2019 |access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref> On September 30, an exclusive photo featuring Liu as a soldier in the Imperial Army was released on Empire's upcoming ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker]]'' issue.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/mulan-disney-remake-david-lean-akira-kurosawa/ |title=Mulan Live-Action Remake Taking 'David Lean Or Kurosawa Approach'- Exclusive Image |last=Travis |first=Ben |date=September 30, 2019 |website=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |access-date=September 30, 2019}}</ref> On October 24, a prequel novel written by writer [[Grace Lin]] was announced along with a preview being made available online. Entitled ''Mulan: Before the Sword'', the novel was announced to be released on February 11, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/books/2019/10/24/grace-lin-mulan-novel-cover-excerpt/ |title=Exclusive preview: Grace Lin fashions a gorgeous original Mulan novel |last=Canfield |first=David |date=October 29, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=February 17, 2020}}</ref> On November 4, a video clip filmed during a Toho cinema preview was leaked online, featuring new shots of Mulan as a warrior battling fiercely and taking off her hair band.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tieba.baidu.com/p/6324507746/ |title=New shots and new lines from Mulan |date=November 4, 2019 |website=[[Baidu]] |access-date=November 4, 2019}}</ref> On November 6, Liu was featured as one of the 25 stars of Next Gen Talent 2019 nominated by ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' with two new studio stills released concurrently.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/next-gen-talent-2019-hollywoods-rising-young-stars-revealed-1250276/ |title=Next Gen Talent 2019: Hollywood's Rising Young Stars Revealed |last=Elise Sandberg |first=Bryn |date=November 6, 2019 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=November 6, 2019}}</ref> On November 20, the Japanese theatrical poster was released online.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/movies/comments/dz0cjv/japanese_poster_of_disneys_liveaction_movie_mulan/ |title=Japanese Poster of Disney's live-action movie Mulan |date=November 20, 2019 |website=[[Reddit]] |access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> On December 5, the official trailer was released with dual versions: the Chinese Weibo debuted a shorter version with different cut and a few shots that were not featured in the US version.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} On January 26, 2020, 6 individual character posters were released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/mulan-character-posters-liu-yifei-donnie-yen/#mulan-character-poster-liu-yifei|title=These New 'Mulan' Character Posters Will Make a Fan Out of You|first=Allie|last=Gemmill|work=[[Collider]]|date=January 26, 2020|accessdate=February 23, 2020}}</ref> On February 2, 2020, the final trailer was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/mulan-final-trailer-puts-villains-in-the-spotlight-video/|title=\u2018Mulan': Final Trailer Puts Villains in the Spotlight (Video)|first=Jeremy|last=Fuster|work=[[The Wrap]]|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Mulan'' had its world premiere at the [[Dolby Theatre]] in Hollywood on March 9, 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mulan-first-reactions-premiere-1283199 |title= 'Mulan': First Reactions from the Premiere |date=March 9, 2020 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> It had been originally set for a November 2, 2018, release but was delayed, with ''[[The Nutcracker and the Four Realms]]'' taking its slot.<ref name=\"FindingMulan\" /> It was then scheduled to be released in the United States on March 27, 2020,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/mulan-reboot-release-date-pushed-back-1202714825/ |title='Mulan' Live-Action Reboot Pushed Back to 2020 |last=Khatchatourian |first=Maane |date=March 1, 2018 |work=Variety |access-date=March 1, 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180302162410/http://variety.com/2018/film/news/mulan-reboot-release-date-pushed-back-1202714825/ |archive-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"NewRelease\">{{Cite news |last1=McClintock |first1=Pamela |last2=Couch |first2=Aaron |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/live-action-mulan-pushed-back-more-a-year-spring-2020-1090015 |title=Live-Action 'Mulan' Pushed Back More Than a Year to Spring 2020 |date=March 1, 2018 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616053315/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/live-action-mulan-pushed-back-more-a-year-spring-2020-1090015 |archive-date=June 16, 2018 |access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> but was delayed again due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mulan-release-pushed-back-coronavirus-pandemic-1284275|title='Mulan' Release Pushed Back Amid Coronavirus Pandemic|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Mia|last=Galuppo|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The film is scheduled to be released on July 24, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/black-widow-mulan-nab-new-release-dates-jungle-cruise-delayed-a-year-1286854|title='Black Widow,' 'Mulan' Land New 2020 Release Dates, 'Jungle Cruise' Delayed a Year|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Pamela |last=McClintock  |archive-date= April 3, 2020|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nA call to boycott the film began when Liu Yifei reshared an image posted by Chinese newspaper ''[[People's Daily]]''. The image included a quote from Chinese reporter [[List of August 2019 Hong Kong protests#12\u201314 August police brutality protests|Fu Guohao]] who worked for the ''[[Global Times]]'' and was subsequently assaulted by protesters during the [[2019 Hong Kong anti-extradition bill protests]]: \"I support Hong Kong police. You can beat me now. What a shame for Hong Kong.\" This sparked international controversy, with Liu being accused of supporting [[police brutality]]. The hashtag, #BoycottMulan, has since started trending supporting a boycott of the movie.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ramzy |first=Austin |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/14/world/asia/hong-kong-airport-protests.html |title=Soul Searching Among Hong Kong Protesters After Chaos at Airport |date=August 14, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818034516/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/14/world/asia/hong-kong-airport-protests.html |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Yeung |first=Jessie |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/16/asia/china-mulan-actor-protests-intl-hnk-trnd/index.html |title=Hong Kong protesters call for 'Mulan' boycott after star went public in support of police |date=August 16, 2019 |website=[[CNN]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818081756/https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/16/asia/china-mulan-actor-protests-intl-hnk-trnd/index.html |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49373276 |title=Liu Yifei: Mulan boycott urged after star backs HK police |date=August 16, 2019 |website=[[BBC]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818003707/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-49373276 |archive-date=August 18, 2019 |access-date=August 16, 2019}}</ref> In response to the controversy, Liu was not present at the 2019 [[D23 Expo]], which gave fans an exclusive sneak peek of the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/mulan-cast-d23-boycottmulan-1203311115/ |title='Mulan' Star Crystal Yifei Liu Skips D23 Amid International Controversy |last=Nissen |first=Dano |date=August 24, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 27, 2020, film producer Jason T. Reed said that Mulan's love interest [[List of Disney's Mulan characters#Li Shang|Captain Li Shang]] was dropped in response to the [[Me Too movement]]. In his statement, he explained that \"having a commanding officer that is also the sexual love interest was very uncomfortable and we didn\u2019t think it was appropriate\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://collider.com/mulan-li-shang-not-in-live-action-remake-reason-why/|title='Mulan': Why Captain Li Shang Isn't in the Live-Action Remake|last=Szany|first=Wendy Lee|work=Collider|date=February 27, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> The reasoning behind the removal was met with social media backlash from fans of the original film and members of the [[LGBTQ]] community, who deemed Shang's relationship with Mulan's male [[alter ego]] Ping to be [[bisexual]].<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news||last=Maleh|first=Linda|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lindamaleh/2020/02/28/disney-blames-metoo-for-li-shangs-absence-from-mulan-in-new-controversy/#2c41d8e95965|title=Disney Blames #MeToo For Li Shang's Absence From 'Mulan' In New Controversy|work=Forbes|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-51707188|title=Mulan: Disney drop character following #MeToo movement|publisher=BBC News|date=March 2, 2020|accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref> Reed was initially surprised by criticism of Shang's removal, but acknowledged that the character had become a \"LGBTQ icon\",<ref name=\"Vogue\">{{cite news|last=Rearick|first=Lauren|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/mulan-love-interest-li-shang-reportedly-split-two-characters-metoo|title=Mulan\" Love Interest Li Shang Was Reportedly Split Into Two Characters Because of MeToo|work=Teen Vogue|date=February 28, 2020|accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref> and clarified that Shang's role would be served by two new characters, Commander Tung and Chen Honghui.<ref name=\"Forbes\"/><ref name=\"Vogue\"/>\n\n==Future==\nIn April 2020, it was announced that a Mulan sequel is in development at Disney with Chris Bender, Jason T. Reed and Jake Weiner returning as producers for sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fullcirclecinema.com/2020/04/18/mulan-2-early-development-disney/|title=\u2018Mulan 2\u2019 Reportedly In Early Development At Disney|magazine=Full Circle Cinema|last=Campbell|first=Jacob|date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://movies.disney.com/mulan-2020}}\n* {{IMDb title|4566758}}\n\n{{Disney's Mulan}}\n{{Disney Princess}}\n{{Disney's live-action adaptations of animated franchises}}\n{{Niki Caro}}\n{{Rick Jaffa and Amanda Silver}}\n\n[[Category:2020 3D films]]\n[[Category:2020s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2020s feminist films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American action adventure films]]\n[[Category:American action films]]\n[[Category:American adventure films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American martial arts films]]\n[[Category:American war films]]\n[[Category:Cross-dressing in American films]]\n[[Category:Disney film remakes]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Film remakes]]\n[[Category:Films about sexism]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films based on adaptations]]\n[[Category:Films based on multiple works]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Niki Caro]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harry Gregson-Williams]]\n[[Category:Films set in Imperial China]]\n[[Category:Films shot in China]]\n[[Category:Films shot in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Rick Jaffa and Amanda Silver]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Mulan (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Period action films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:War adventure films]]\n", "name_user": "ClaudeDavid", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed grammatical error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mulan_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "Carles Puyol", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Spanish name|Puyol|Saforcada}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Carles Puyol\n| image = Puyol2011.jpg\n| image_size = 200\n| caption = Puyol playing for [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in 2011\n| fullname = Carles Puyol Saforcada<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf|title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of players|publisher=FIFA|page=29|format=PDF|date=4 June 2010|accessdate=13 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=Bio>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/075/75.html|title=Carles PUYOL Saforcada|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|4|13|df=y}}<ref name=Bio/>\n| birth_place = [[La Pobla de Segur]], Spain<ref name=Bio2>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/futbol/20140515/54407940003/carles-puyol-la-pobla-de-segur-reivindica-hijo-mas-universal.html|title=Carles Puyol: La Pobla de Segur reivindica el car\u00e1cter y la fortaleza de su hijo m\u00e1s universal|trans-title=Carles Puyol: La Pobla de Segur claims character and strength of its most universal son|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|last=L\u00f3pez|first=Antoni|language=es|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n| height = 1.78 m<ref name=Bio/>\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 1992\u20131995 | youthclubs1 = Pobla de Segur\n| youthyears2 = 1995\u20131996 | youthclubs2 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n| years1 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs1 = [[FC Barcelona C|Barcelona C]] | caps1 = | goals1 = \n| years2 = 1997\u20131999 | clubs2 = [[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]] | caps2 = 89 | goals2 = 6\n| years3 = 1999\u20132014 | clubs3 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps3 = 392 | goals3 = 12\n| totalcaps = 481 | totalgoals = 18\n| nationalyears1 = 1995 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 3 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2000 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps2 = 4 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2000 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-23 football team|Spain U23]] | nationalcaps3 = 5 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2000\u20132013 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps4 = 100 | nationalgoals4 = 3\n| nationalyears5 = 2001\u20132013 | nationalteam5 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] | nationalcaps5 = 6 | nationalgoals5 = 0\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update = \n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport | Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2008|2008 Austria-Switzerland]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 South Africa]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[FIFA Confederations Cup 2009|2009 South Africa]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[FIFA Confederations Cup 2013|2013 Brazil]]|}}\n}}\n'''Carles Puyol Saforcada''' ({{IPA-ca|\u02c8ka\u027el\u0259s pu\u02c8j\u0254l i s\u0250fu\u027e\u02c8ka\u00f0\u0250<!--Western Catalan pronunciation-->}}; born 13 April 1978) is a Spanish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]]. Mainly a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]], he could also play on [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|either flank]], mostly as a right-back,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/spain/players_to_watch/3594557.stm|title=Carles Puyol|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=25 May 2004|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> and was regarded as one of the best defenders of all time.<ref name=Grit>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/soccer/world-cup-2010/writers/ben_lyttleton/07/09/puyol/index.html|title=Puyol anchors Spanish defense with combination of hard work, grit|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|last=Lyttleton|first=Ben|date=9 July 2010|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nA [[List of one-club men in association football|one-club man]], he served as the long-time [[Captain (association football)|team captain]] for his only club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] after taking over from [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]] in August 2004, and went on to appear in 593 competitive matches for the club and win 18 major titles, notably six [[La Liga]] trophies and three [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] titles.\n\nA [[Spain national football team|Spain international]] on [[List of footballers with 100 or more caps|100 occasions]], Puyol was part of the squad that won the [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] and the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] tournaments. In the latter competition's semi-final, he scored the only goal of the game against [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/puyol-intl.html|title=Carles Puyol Saforcada \u2013 Century of International Appearances|publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]|accessdate=1 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[La Pobla de Segur]], [[Province of Lleida|Lleida]], [[Catalonia]],<ref name=Bio2/> Puyol started playing football for his hometown club as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], but after injury problems with his shoulder he switched to [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He said that in his youth, \"My parents were skeptical about me becoming a footballer and encouraged me to study.\"<ref name=Mitten>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/puyols-love-of-labour-not-lost-on-fans-478129.html|title=Puyol's love of labour not lost on fans|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|last=Mitten|first=Andy|date=14 May 2006|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref> In 1995, he joined [[FC Barcelona]]'s youth system at [[La Masia]], switching positions again, to play as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]]; two years later, he started playing for [[FC Barcelona B|the club's B-team]], occupying the position of [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right-back]].\n\nIn 1998, Barcelona accepted an offer from [[M\u00e1laga CF]] to sell Puyol, who was behind [[Frank de Boer]] and [[Michael Reiziger]] in the pecking order. However, he refused to leave after seeing his best friend [[Xavi]] make his first-team debut.<ref name=Grit/>\n\n[[Louis van Gaal]] promoted Puyol to the first team the following year, and he made his [[La Liga]] debut on 2 October 1999 in a 2\u20130 away win against [[Real Valladolid]]. After that he successfully made another conversion, now to [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]]. During the 2003 off-season, as Barcelona was immersed in a financial crisis, [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] showed interest in acquiring Puyol's services,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/3134299.stm|title=Man Utd move for Puyol|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 August 2003|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> but no move ever materialised; two years later, the player extended his contract for a further five seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4272140.stm|title=Barca skipper Puyol pens new deal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=22 September 2005|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carles Puyol 18abr2007.jpg|thumb|upright|Puyol in a 2007 La Liga match against [[Getafe CF|Getafe]]]]\nPuyol was named club [[Captain (association football)|captain]] at the end of [[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u201304]], after the retirement of [[Luis Enrique (footballer)|Luis Enrique]]. He continued to be a defensive cornerstone for ''Bar\u00e7a'', being awarded the \"Best European right-back\" award by [[UEFA]] in 2002 (amongst other individual accolades), and helping the Catalans win two consecutive league titles. In [[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u201306]] he appeared in a total of 52 official games, including 12 in [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|that season]]'s [[UEFA Champions League]] which ended in victory against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], the Spaniards second European Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/4773353.stm|title=Barcelona 2\u20131 Arsenal|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 May 2006|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 2008, Puyol made his 400th appearance in all competitions for Barcelona's first team in a [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group stage match]] against [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada08-09/09/n080916105269.html|title=The captain makes it to 400 games|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=16 September 2008|accessdate=18 September 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120731074335/http://www.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada08-09/09/n080916105269.html|archivedate=31 July 2012}}</ref> In the [[2008\u201309 La Liga|league season]], despite injury problems, he contributed to the team by appearing in 28 matches and helped them win another league title. His only goal came against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] in ''[[El Cl\u00e1sico]]'' at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium|Santiago Bernab\u00e9u]] on 2 May 2009 which finished with a resounding 6\u20132 away win,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/02/la-liga-real-madrid-barcelona|title=Barcelona run riot at Real Madrid and put Chelsea on notice|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|last=Lowe|first=Sid|date=2 May 2009|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> and he [[goal celebration|celebrated his goal]] by kissing his [[Senyera|Catalan flag]] armband in front of the incensed Madrid fans;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2017/04/24/58fe5ed8ca47413f548b461c.html|title=Real Madrid-Barcelona: Celebrations in enemy territory|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018}}</ref> he was essential to the team winning the [[2009 UEFA Super Cup]], the [[2009 UEFA Champions League Final|2009 Champions League]] and the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup]], appearing in nearly 100 official matches, and described the club as \"the team who every Catalan child wants to play for... I am living the dream playing football for Bar\u00e7a and it is my dream to retire playing here.\"<ref name=Mitten/>\n\n[[File:Carles Puyol Joan Gamper-Tr.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Puyol as Barcelona captain (wearing his [[Senyera|Catalan]] armband) in 2008]]\nOn 13 November 2010, Puyol played his 500th game in all competitions for Barcelona's first team in a domestic league tie against [[Villarreal CF]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/carles-puyol-number-500/|title=Carles Puyol: number 500|publisher=Total Bar\u00e7a|date=13 November 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306155940/http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/carles-puyol-number-500/|archivedate=6 March 2014}}</ref> He struggled again with injuries during [[2010\u201311 La Liga|the campaign]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada10-11/09/01/n100901112669.html|title=Puyol injury shock|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=1 September 2010|accessdate=18 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130122214924/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada10-11/09/01/n100901112669.html|archivedate=22 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/858955/barcelona-lose-captain-carles-puyol-to-groin-injury?cc=5739|title=Barcelona lose Puyol to groin injury|publisher=[[ESPN FC|ESPN Soccernet]]|date=30 December 2010|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/924816/barcelona-captain-carles-puyol-to-undergo-knee-surgery?cc=5739|title=Knee surgery for Barca captain Puyol|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=31 May 2011|accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> but still appeared in 28 competitive matches while again winning the league and the Champions League; he played six minutes in [[2011 UEFA Champions League Final|the final]] of the latter competition, a 3\u20131 victory over Manchester United.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/13576522|title=Barcelona 3\u20131 Man Utd|publisher=BBC Sport|last=McNulty|first=Phil|date=28 May 2011|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince the defeat to [[Inter Milan]] in the [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|2009\u201310 Champions League]] semi-final, Puyol went on to take part in 56 official matches for Barcelona without losing, a run that only ended on 11 January 2012 at [[CA Osasuna]] (2\u20133 loss).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/50-games-straight-without-losing-with-puyol-on-the-pitch|title=50 games straight without losing with Puyol on the pitch|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=16 January 2012|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref> Additionally, he scored two goals in [[2011\u201312 Copa del Rey|the season]]'s [[Copa del Rey]], against Real Madrid (2\u20131 away win, 4\u20133 on aggregate) and [[Valencia CF]] (1\u20131 away, 3\u20131 aggregate).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=335877&cc=5739|title=Barca fight back at the Bernabeu|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=18 January 2012|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/match-archive/2011-2012/copa-del-rey/1-2-1st-leg/valencia_fc-barcelona|title=Valencia \u2013 FC Barcelona: Draw with some shine (1\u20131)|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=1 February 2012|accessdate=21 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 October 2012, in the late stages of a [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League|Champions League group stage encounter]] at [[S.L. Benfica]], his first game upon recovering from a knee ligament injury suffered against [[Getafe CF]], Puyol dislocated his elbow after landing awkwardly in a [[corner kick]] challenge. He was initially expected to be sidelined for two months<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1870771.html|title=Elbow injury sends Puyol back to Bar\u00e7a sidelines|publisher=UEFA|date=3 October 2012|accessdate=3 October 2012}}</ref> but fully recovered in one.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.20minutos.es/deportes/noticia/puyol-recibe-alta-barca-1650257/0/|title=Puyol recibe el alta seis semanas despu\u00e9s de la luxaci\u00f3n en el codo|trans-title=Puyol is released six weeks after elbow sprain|newspaper=[[20 minutos]]|language=es|date=16 November 2012|accessdate=5 February 2019}}</ref> On 18 December Barcelona renewed his contract, extending it until 30 June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/carles-puyol-xavi-hernandez-and-leo-messi-renew-their-contract-with-fc-barcelona|title=Bar\u00e7a has renewed the contracts of Carles Puyol, Xavi Hern\u00e1ndez and Leo Messi|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=8 January 2013}}</ref> In June of the following year he again underwent surgery on his right knee, his sixth operation as a professional,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sport.es/es/noticias/barca/carles-puyol-cuando-quirofano-salon-casa-2423889|title=Carles Puyol, cuando el quir\u00f3fano es el sal\u00f3n de casa|trans-title=Carles Puyol, when surgery room is the living room|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|last=Ortu\u00f1o|first=Xavier|language=es|date=18 June 2013|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref> which led to thoughts of early retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=2089699.html|title=Retirement on Puyol's mind after surgery|publisher=FIFA|date=31 May 2013|accessdate=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Uniforme Puyol.jpg|thumb|right|Puyol's jersey and boots in the [[FC Barcelona Museum]]]]\nOn 2 March 2014, Puyol surpassed [[Migueli]] to go second in [[List of FC Barcelona records and statistics#Most appearances|Bar\u00e7a's all-time league appearances table]], behind only Xavi, and scored the third goal in a 4\u20131 home win against [[UD Almer\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2014/03/03/en/football/barcelona/1393868626.html|title=Puyol moves second in Bar\u00e7a league appearances list|newspaper=Marca|date=2 March 2014|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref> Two days later, although he still had two more years in his contract, he announced that he would leave Barcelona at the end of [[2013\u201314 La Liga|the season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/carles-puyol-anuncia-que-deixa-el-barca-a-final-de-temporada|title=Carles Puyol announces he is leaving FC Barcelona at the end of the season|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=4 March 2014|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2573348/Carles-Puyol-retires-He-brave-leader-heroic-career.html|title=Puyol is a brave leader who dismissed theories that strikers get all the glory, his career was nothing short of heroic|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|last=Jenson|first=Pete|date=4 March 2014|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> He said, \"After my last two major operations, I find it is taking me a lot of effort to reach the level required here, even more than myself and the surgeons thought necessary. That's the reason I have reached this decision\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2067439.html|title=Puyol announces he is to leave Barcelona|publisher=UEFA|date=4 March 2014|accessdate=6 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nBarcelona bid farewell to Puyol on 15 May 2014, after a fifteen-year career in the first team (ten as captain) that brought him 21 titles. At a packed Auditori 1899, his teammates, ex-teammates, presidents and coaches paid tribute to him, and he said, \"I\u2019ve lived the dream of so many young kids, doing what I most enjoy in life, playing football and training\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/puyol-i-came-here-as-a-boy-and-i-leave-with-a-family|title=Puyol: \"I came here as a boy and I leave with a family\"|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref> He announced his retirement shortly after at the age of 36 but stayed connected to his only club; he was immediately appointed [[director of football]] [[Andoni Zubizarreta]]'s assistant.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20140531/fc-barcelona/carles-puyol-sera-el-segundo-de-zubizarreta_54408533450.html|title=Carles Puyol ser\u00e1 el 'segundo' de Zubizarreta|trans-title=Carles Puyol to be Zubizarreta's 'second'|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|last1=Polo|first1=Fernando|last2=Poqu\u00ed|first2=Joan|language=es|date=31 May 2014|accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref> He resigned in January 2015, shortly after Zubizarreta was fired.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/liga/2014-2015/barcelona-sack-director-of-football-andoni-zubizarreta_sto4535140/story.shtml|title=Carles Puyol resigns as Barcelona sack director of football Andoni Zubizarreta|publisher=[[Eurosport]]|last=Adams|first=Tom|date=6 January 2015|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Puyol rejected an offer to become Barcelona's [[sporting director]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49833844|title=Barcelona: Carles Puyol rejects sports director offer|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 September 2019|accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Puyol Catalunya - Argentina.jpg|thumb|left|Puyol playing for [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] in a 2009 friendly match against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] at [[Camp Nou]].]]\nPuyol won his first [[Cap (sport)|cap]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on 15 November 2000 against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2010/07/09/deportes/1278626402_850215.html|title=\"Sab\u00eda que iba a ser gol\"|trans-title=\"I knew it was going in\"|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Mart\u00edn|first=Luis|language=es|date=9 July 2010|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref> and remained a regular fixture in the following years. He played for his country at the [[Football at the 2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Olympics]], [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2004]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=181041.html#saez+spain+squad|title=S\u00e1ez selects Spain squad|publisher=UEFA|date=20 May 2004|accessdate=7 May 2016}}</ref> [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]], [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]].\n\nPuyol started every game except one at Euro 2008, and Spain's defence only conceded two goals in his five games. They won [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|the final]] against [[Germany national football team|Germany]], and he was named in the ''Team of the Tournament'' alongside his defensive partner, [[Carlos Marchena]] of Valencia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2008/06/30/mas_futbol/1214776806_850215.html|title=Xavi, elegido jugador de la Eurocopa 2008|trans-title=Xavi, voted player of Euro 2008|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|last=Garc\u00eda|first=\u00d3scar|language=es|date=30 June 2008|accessdate=13 February 2019}}</ref> He started in three out of five matches at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]], and acted as captain when [[Iker Casillas]] was rested for the last group stage match.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2009/06/22/mas_futbol/1245621619_850215.html|title=Sin Casillas, Xavi le cedi\u00f3 la capitan\u00eda a Puyol|trans-title=Without Casillas, Xavi gave captaincy to Puyol|newspaper=Diario AS|last=Maroto|first=Joaqu\u00edn|language=es|date=22 June 2009|accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref> They finished third, and Puyol was included in the ''Team of the Tournament'' with four of his teammates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/2009/06/30/futbol/copa_confederaciones/1246369263.html|title=Puyol, Capdevila, Villa y Torres, en el once ideal de la web en la FIFA|trans-title=Puyol, Capdevila, Villa and Torres, in FIFA's web All-Star IX|newspaper=Marca|language=es|date=30 June 2009|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2010 World Cup in [[South Africa]], Puyol started every match and played almost every minute (he was replaced by Marchena in the 84th minute of the quarter-final against [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=264118&cc=5739&ver=global|title=Villa saves Spain after penalty drama|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=3 July 2010|accessdate=8 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706023637/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=264118&cc=5739&ver=global|archivedate=6 July 2010}}</ref> He scored the only goal in the semi-final with Germany, a powerful header from a corner taken by Barcelona teammate [[Xavi]], which sent the national team through to their first [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=264121&cc=5739&ver=global|title=Puyol heads Spain into final|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=7 July 2010|accessdate=8 July 2010}}</ref> In the [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|decisive match]], he played the full 120 minutes as the side defeated the Netherlands 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_64/default.stm|title=Netherlands 0\u20131 Spain (aet)|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|date=11 July 2010|accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August 2010, aged 32, Puyol announced that he would continue to represent the national team for at least another two years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/02/sports/soccer/02sportsbriefs-puyol.html|title=Puyol to keep playing for Spain|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=2 August 2010|accessdate=2 August 2010}}</ref> He missed [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] due to a knee injury sustained in a league game against [[RCD Espanyol]] in early May, which required surgery and five to six weeks' recuperation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1065289/spain's-carles-puyol-set-to-miss-euro-2012-due-to-knee-surgery?cc=5739|title=Puyol facing fitness fight|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nPuyol played his 100th international on 6 February 2013, captaining Spain to a 3\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win over [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2012_13/amistosos_seleccion/4/spa_uru/|title=Campe\u00f3n hasta en los simulacros|trans-title=Champions even in drills|newspaper=Marca|last=Aldunate|first=Ramiro|language=es|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2013/02/06/futbol/seleccion/1360113641.html|title=100 veces Puyol|trans-title=100 times Puyol|newspaper=Marca|last=Lara|first=Miguel \u00c1ngel|language=es|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"Puyol is the key, not just because he is one of the best defenders in the world but because of his character. He never lets up.\"\n | source =&nbsp;\u2014[[Xavi]]<ref name=Lowe>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/apr/29/barcelona.championsleague|title=Puyol returns to give Barcelona lift and leadership|newspaper=The Guardian|last=Lowe|first=Sid|date=29 April 2008|accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref>\n | width  = 25%\n | align  = left\n | style  = padding:10px;\n}}\nPuyol was known for his commanding presence in the air, his composure on the ball and his intense commitment and ruggedness. According to Barcelona's head doctor, he was \"the strongest, who has the quickest reactions, and who has the most explosive strength.\"<ref name=Grit/> Club fans referred to him as \"The Wall\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/sports/soccer/09iht-WCSOCCER.html?scp=1&sq=puyol&st=cse|title=Puyol, a star on defense, wins it with offense|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Hughes|first=Rob|date=8 July 2010|accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Nadal]], who played with him for a short period of time, said, \"Carles plays with maturity, has great positional sense, and above all, has pride in his shirt.\"<ref name=Grit/>\n\nPuyol was also known for his leadership and work ethic. He often continued training alone after the end of a team practice session or on days off.<ref name=Lowe/> He said in 2010, \"I don't have [[Rom\u00e1rio]]'s technique, [Marc] [[Marc Overmars|Overmars]]' pace or [Patrick] [[Patrick Kluivert|Kluivert]]'s strength. But I work harder than the others. I'm like the student who is not as clever, but revises for his exams and does OK in the end.\"<ref name=Grit/>\n\nFellow defender [[Gerard Piqu\u00e9]] said: \"He's someone who, even if you're winning 3\u20130 and there's a few seconds left in the game will shout at the top of his voice at you if he thinks your concentration is going.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sport/soccer/2010-07-11-defending-the-caveman/|title=Defending the caveman|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (South Africa)|The Sunday Times]]|last=Hawkey|first=Ian|date=11 July 2010|accessdate=17 October 2018}}</ref> A former team-mate said, \"Even four goals down he thinks we can still win\",<ref name=Lowe/> and another described him as \"a pain in the arse\" but added \"that's exactly what we need\".<ref name=Lowe/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/carlos-puyol-announcement-no-obvious-successor-for-barcelona-legend-and-master-of-reinvention-9169174.html|title=Carlos Puyol announcement: No obvious successor for Barcelona legend and master of reinvention|newspaper=The Independent|last=Jenson|first=Pete|date=4 March 2014|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/club/barcelona/83/blog/post/1951350/all-time-greatest-captain-carles-puyol-the-inspiring-leader|title=Carles Puyol: The inspiring leader|publisher=ESPN FC|date=27 August 2014|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Puyol 2010 02 02.jpg|thumb|upright|Puyol in 2010]]\nPuyol's long shaggy hair was a distinctive feature throughout his career. Barcelona manager Van Gaal suggested he get it cut when the player was 19, immediately after his first training session with the senior players: \"What's your problem, can't you afford the money for a haircut?\", Van Gaal asked him in his office. \"I said nothing,\" Puyol remembered, \"and to this day have kept my hair as it is.<ref name=Grit/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/players/player=177914/profile.html|title=Carles Puyol|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Puyol said that when not working, he leads \"a very quiet life... I've not been to a nightclub in [[Barcelona]] for years either. When I go out, I stay in a restaurant with my friends.\"<ref name=Mitten/>\n\nPuyol's father, Josep, died in a farming accident in late 2006 while Carles was on his way to play a match against [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]. He was informed of the news by coach [[Frank Rijkaard]] upon landing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/Puyol/baja/muerte/padre/accidente/elpepidep/20061104elpepidep_6/Tes|title=Puyol es baja tras la muerte de su padre en un accidente|trans-title=Puyol out after his father died in accident|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|last1=Visa|first1=Llu\u00eds|last2=Hermida|first2=Xos\u00e9|language=es|date=4 November 2006|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref> He said that this, combined with an injury led to a dark period, with Spanish national team physio Ra\u00fal Mart\u00ednez eventually coming to Barcelona: in the player's words, \"...[he] gave me a great telling off. He made me react, and I began to try to be more cheerful, and not overwhelmed by it all.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/deportes/500/deja/elpepudep/20101115elpepudep_10/Tes|title=500 m\u00e1s y lo deja|trans-title=500 more and he's through|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|last=Mart\u00edn|first=Lu\u00eds|language=es|date=15 November 2010|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, Puyol told [[Goal (website)|Goal.com]]: \"I do not like to go out much, although it is good to disconnect and I like to read.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/03/15/1156551/carles-puyol-on-life-leadership-and-trophies-at-barcelona|title=Carles Puyol on life, leadership and trophies at Barcelona|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=15 March 2009|accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref> In September 2010, he started a relationship with [[Model (person)|model]] Malena Costa. In October of that year, he scored through a header in a 2\u20131 home win against [[Valencia CF]] and dedicated the goal to her by making a heart symbol with both hands. \u201cI dedicate the goal to my girlfriend\u201d, he said after the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/picture-of-the-day-celebrations/|title=Picture of the day: Celebrations|publisher=Total Bar\u00e7a|date=18 October 2010|accessdate=3 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021072657/http://www.totalbarca.com/2010/news/picture-of-the-day-celebrations/|archivedate=21 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Puyol paid \u20ac30,000 for specialist private treatment for [[Miki Roqu\u00e9]], a footballer from his home province who was suffering from pelvic cancer. However, the latter died in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2012/06/25/mas_futbol/1340575234_850215.html|title=Carles Puyol coste\u00f3 el tratamiento de Miki Roqu\u00e9|trans-title=Carles Puyol paid for Miki Roqu\u00e9's treatment|newspaper=Diario AS|language=es|date=25 June 2012|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nPuyol started a relationship with [[Vanessa Lorenzo]] in 2012. The couple had two daughters, Manuela (born 2014) and Mar\u00eda (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/carles-puyols-daughter-manuela-is-born|title=Carles Puyol's daughter Manuela is born|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=25 January 2014|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sport.es/es/noticias/fuera-de-juego/puyol-anuncia-nacimiento-hija-maria-4798732|title=Puyol anuncia el nacimiento de su hija Mar\u00eda|trans-title=Puyol announces birth of his daughter Mar\u00eda|newspaper=Sport|language=es|date=7 January 2016|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nPuyol was invited by Iranian television channel [[IRIB TV3]] to provide commentary on the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] match between Iran and Spain on 20 June 2018 in a programme hosted by [[Adel Ferdosipour]], but was not allowed in the studio. According to news website [[Entekhab]], the former player said that he had been told by the [[Islamic Republic of Iran Broadcasting]] that he could not appear in the programme \"because of his looks (long hair)\"; the veteran channel director had been replaced by one closer to Iran's ultra-religious hardliners weeks before, and this incident ultimately led to some ridicule within Iran on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-trending-44577659|title=World Cup 2018: Footballer's hair 'too wild' for Iranian TV|publisher=[[BBC News]]|last=Rannard|first=Georgina|date=23 June 2018|accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/la-trajectoria-de-carles-puyol-al-detall|title=In-depth look at Carles Puyol's career|publisher=FC Barcelona|date=3 April 2014|accessdate=2 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605075900/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/la-trajectoria-de-carles-puyol-al-detall|archive-date=5 June 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/carles-puyol-saforcada/325/|title=Puyol|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=2 June 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[Copa del Rey]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[FC Barcelona B|Barcelona B]]\n|[[1996\u201397 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1996\u201397]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]\n|1||1||colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||1||1\n|-\n|[[1997\u201398 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1997\u201398]]\n|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|42||3||colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||42||3\n|-\n|!colspan=\"2\"|[[1998\u201399 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1998\u201399]]\n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n\n|38||2||colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||38||2\n|-\n|!colspan=\"2\"|[[1999\u20132000 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|1999\u20132000]]\n|Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B\n|8||0||colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||8||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!89!!6!!colspan=\"6\"|\u2014||89!!6\n|-\n|rowspan=\"16\"|[[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]\n|[[1999\u20132000 FC Barcelona season|1999\u20132000]]\n|rowspan=\"15\"|[[La Liga]]\n|24||0||5||0||8<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"UCL\">Appearances in [[UEFA Champions League]]</ref>||0||0||0||37||0\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 FC Barcelona season|2000\u201301]]\n|17||0||2||0||5<ref group=\"lower-alpha\" name=\"B\">Three appearances in [[2000\u201301 UEFA