otballers]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2004 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2008 players]]\n[[Category:2009 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Olympic footballers of Spain]]\n[[Category:Footballers at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in football]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Spain]]\n[[Category:UEFA European Championship-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:Catalonia international footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Teodor Munte", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carles_Puyol"}
{"title_page": "Association de Juristes Maliennes", "text_new": "The '''Association de Juristes Maliennes''' ('''AJM'''), or '''Association of Women Jurists of Mali''', is an organization which tries to promote and protect [[women's rights]] in Malian law. An apolitical organization, the AJM's membership consists of around fifty women lawyers, solicitors, magistrates and judges.<ref name=EngelHesseling/> It is a member organization of [[Groupe Pivot / Droits et Citoyennet\u00e9 des Femmes]] (GP/DCF).<ref>Kether R. Hayden, [https://www.oxy.edu/sites/default/files/assets/UEP/Comps/2008/kether%20hayden%20comps%20final%20draft%20april%2018.pdf Women's Associations in Mali: Empowerment, Leadership, and Political Mobilization], Student thesis, 18 April 2008.</ref> [[Fatoumata Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 Diarra]] is a past president.<ref name=\"Sheldon2005\">{{cite book|author=Kathleen Sheldon|title=Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HMAeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA23|year=2005|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6547-1|page=23|chapter=Association de Juristes Maliennes}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe AJM was officially established in 1988.<ref name=EngelHesseling>{{cite book|editor1=J. A. Andersson|editor2=M. Breusers|title=Kinship structures and enterprising actors: Anthropological essays on development|chapter=Women and law in Mali|author1=Marijke van der Engel|author2=Gerti Hesseling|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/9723/ASC_1247243_130.pdf?sequence=1|pages=303, 310\u201311}}</ref> In the 1990s it used funding from [[international aid agencies]] to provide mobile legal clinics to rural [[women in Mali]], and broadcast a radio program, 'La Voix des Femmes'.<ref name=\"Sheldon2005\"/> AJM lawyers, with the help of the American Embassy, published a 1995 study of discriminatory elements in Malian law,<ref>Groupe d Appui \u00e0 la R\u00e9forme Juridique, ''La situation de la femme dans le droit positif malien et ses perspectives d'\u00e9volution'', 1995.</ref> The study was \"a major impetus for altering discriminatory articles in the law\".<ref name=EngelHesseling/>\n\nIn November 2014, the AJM reported over 150 victims of [[forced marriage]] and [[sexual violence]].<ref> Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada, [Mali : Forced marriage, including the prevalence of forced marriage, related legislation, state protection, support services and the ability of women to refuse a forced marriage (2012 \u2013 June 2016)], 15 July 2016.</ref> Six organizations, including the AJM, filed a complaint to the [[Bamako Commune III]] Court of First Instance on behalf of 80 victims of rape and sexual violence committed by armed groups during the [[Mali War]] in 2012-13.<ref>M\u00e9gane Ghorbani, [https://www.awid.org/news-and-analysis/mali-no-peace-building-without-women Mali: No Peace Building without Women], [[Association for Women's Rights in Development]], 28 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1988 establishments in Mali]]\n[[Category:Women's organisations based in Mali]]\n[[Category:Malian women jurists|*]]\n[[Category:Legal organizations based in Mali]]\n[[Category:Legal advocacy organizations]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Association de Juristes Maliennes''' ('''AJM'''), or '''Association of Women Jurists of Mali''', is an organization which tries to promote and protect [[women's rights]] in Malian law. An apolitical organization, the AJM's membership consists of around fifty women lawyers, solicitors, magistrates and judges.<ref name=EngelHesseling/> It is a member organization of [[Groupe Pivot / Droits et Citoyennet\u00e9 des Femmes]] (GP/DCF).<ref>Kether R. Hayden, [https://www.oxy.edu/sites/default/files/assets/UEP/Comps/2008/kether%20hayden%20comps%20final%20draft%20april%2018.pdf Women's Associations in Mali: Empowerment, Leadership, and Political Mobilization], Student thesis, 18 April 2008.</ref> [[Fatoumata Demb\u00e9l\u00e9 Diarra]] is a past president.<ref name=\"Sheldon2005\">{{cite book|author=Kathleen Sheldon|title=Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HMAeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA23|year=2005|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6547-1|page=23|chapter=Association de Juristes Maliennes}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe AJM was officially established in 1988.<ref name=EngelHesseling>{{cite book|editor1=J. A. Andersson|editor2=M. Breusers|title=Kinship structures and enterprising actors: Anthropological essays on development|chapter=Women and law in Mali|author1=Marijke van der Engel|author2=Gerti Hesseling|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/9723/ASC_1247243_130.pdf?sequence=1|pages=303, 310\u201311}}</ref> In the 1990s it used funding from international aid agencies to provide mobile legal clinics to rural women in Mali, and broadcast a radio program, 'La Voix des Femmes'.<ref name=\"Sheldon2005\"/> AJM lawyers, with the help of the American Embassy, published a 1995 study of discriminatory elements in Malian law,<ref>Groupe d Appui \u00e0 la R\u00e9forme Juridique, ''La situation de la femme dans le droit positif malien et ses perspectives d'\u00e9volution'', 1995.</ref> The study was \"a major impetus for altering discriminatory articles in the law\".<ref name=EngelHesseling/>\n\nIn November 2014, the AJM reported over 150 victims of [[forced marriage]] and [[sexual violence]].<ref> Immigration and Refugee Board of Canada, [Mali : Forced marriage, including the prevalence of forced marriage, related legislation, state protection, support services and the ability of women to refuse a forced marriage (2012 \u2013 June 2016)], 15 July 2016.</ref> Six organizations, including the AJM, filed a complaint to the [[Bamako Commune III]] Court of First Instance on behalf of 80 victims of rape and sexual violence committed by armed groups during the [[Mali War]] in 2012-13.<ref>M\u00e9gane Ghorbani, [https://www.awid.org/news-and-analysis/mali-no-peace-building-without-women Mali: No Peace Building without Women], [[Association for Women's Rights in Development]], 28 July 2015.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1988 establishments in Mali]]\n[[Category:Women's organisations based in Mali]]\n[[Category:Malian women jurists|*]]\n[[Category:Legal organizations based in Mali]]\n[[Category:Legal advocacy organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Dsp13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:wlinks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Association_de_Juristes_Maliennes"}
{"title_page": "Johann Martin Veith", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Johann Martin Veith\n| image         = Johann Martin Veith.jpg\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    = Johann Martin Veith\n| birth_date    = 9 May 1650\n| birth_place   = [[Schaffhausen]], Switzerland\n| death_date    = 14 April 1717 (aged 67)\n| death_place   = [[Schaffhausen]], Switzerland\n| nationality   = [[Switzerland|Swiss]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = [[Baroque art|Baroque]]\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        =\n}}\n'''Johann Martin Veith''' (9 May 1650{{spaced ndash}}14 April 1717) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Painting|painter]] in the [[Baroque art|Baroque]] style, known for historical, Biblical and mythological scenes.\n\n==Life and work==\nJohann Martin Veith studied art in [[Rome]] and [[Venice]] for ten years, after which he went with the Prince [[Radziwi\u0142\u0142]] to [[Warsaw]], where he worked for two years. Upon his return to Schaffhausen he painted portraits of prominent people as well as scenes from mythology and history in the Venetian style.\n\n==External links==\n* {{HDS|19163|Johann Martin Veith|author=Tapan Bhattacharya}}\n* {{SIKART|4023312|Veith, Johann Martin}}\n* [[Johann Kaspar Fuessli]]: [http://books.google.ch/books?id=-ZEPAAAAQAAJ&hl=de&pg=PA203#v=onepage&q&f=false ''{{lang|de|Geschichte der besten K\u00fcnstler in der Schweiz}}'', Bd. 2, Z\u00fcrich 1769-1774, S. 203\u2013207.]\n* [[Matthew Pilkington]], [[Henry Fuseli]]: [http://books.google.ch/books?id=Sg1BAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA635#v=onepage&q&f=false John Martin Vyth, or Veyth, ''{{lang|en|A Dictionary of Painters: from the revival of the art to the present period}}'', London 1805, S. 635]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Commons category|Johann Martin Veith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veith, Johann Martin}}\n[[Category:1650 births]]\n[[Category:1717 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Schaffhausen]]\n[[Category:Mythological painters]]\n[[Category:17th-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:18th-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:Swiss male painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Johann Martin Veith\n| image         = Johann Martin Veith.jpg\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       =\n| birth_name    = Johann Martin Veith\n| birth_date    = 9 May 1650\n| birth_place   = [[Schaffhausen]], Switzerland\n| death_date    = 14 April 1717 (aged 67)\n| death_place   = [[Schaffhausen]], Switzerland\n| nationality   = [[Switzerland|Swiss]]\n| field         = [[Painting]]\n| training      =\n| movement      = [[Baroque art|Baroque]]\n| works         =\n| patrons       =\n| awards        =\n}}\n'''Johann Martin Veith''' (9 May 1650{{spaced ndash}}14 April 1717) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Painting|painter]] in the [[Baroque art|Baroque]] style, known for historical, Biblical and mythological scenes.\n\n==Life and work==\nJohann Martin Veith studied art in [[Rome]] and [[Venice]] for ten years, after which he went with the Prince [[Radziwi\u0142\u0142]] to [[Warsaw]], where he worked for two years. Upon his return to Schaffhausen he painted portraits of prominent people as well as scenes from mythology and history in the Venetian style.\n\n==External links==\n* {{HDS|19163|Johann Martin Veith|author=Tapan Bhattacharya}}\n* {{SIKART|4023312|Veith, Johann Martin}}\n* [[Johann Kaspar Fuessli]]: [http://books.google.ch/books?id=-ZEPAAAAQAAJ&hl=de&pg=PA203#v=onepage&q&f=false ''{{lang|de|Geschichte der besten K\u00fcnstler in der Schweiz}}'', Bd. 2, Z\u00fcrich 1769-1774, S. 203\u2013207.]\n* [[Matthew Pilkington]], [[Henry Fuseli]]: [http://books.google.ch/books?id=Sg1BAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA635#v=onepage&q&f=false John Martin Vyth, or Veyth, ''{{lang|en|A Dictionary of Painters: from the revival of the art to the present period}}'', London 1805, S. 635]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Commonscat|Johann Martin Veith}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veith, Johann Martin}}\n\n[[Category:1650 births]]\n[[Category:1717 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Schaffhausen]]\n[[Category:Mythological painters]]\n[[Category:17th-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:18th-century Swiss painters]]\n[[Category:Swiss male painters]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johann_Martin_Veith"}
{"title_page": "53rd Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)", "text_new": "{{for|the demolished station serving the IRT Third Avenue Line in Manhattan|53rd Street (IRT Third Avenue Line)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 53 Street \n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = Reopening of 53rd St ESI Station (36965174321).jpg\n| image_caption = Northbound R train arriving at the platform\n| address = 53rd Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11220\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|38|37|N|74|0|55.86|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth south local\n| service_header = Fourth south local header\n| connection = {{Bus icon}} '''[[New York City Transit buses|New York City Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B11}}; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4 (2 in regular service)\n| structure = Underground\n| wifi = yes\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}<ref name=\"Station Opening\" />\n| close_date = {{start date and age|2017|3|27}} (reconstruction)\n| rebuilt = {{start date and age|2017|09|08}}\n| other_exits = Fourth Avenue and 53rd Street, Fourth Avenue and 52nd Street (southbound only)\n| code = 034\n| passengers = 2,378,056<ref name=\"riderref\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = 100.2\n| rank = 196<ref name=\"riderref\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=45th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=59th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''53rd Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at 53rd Street and [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] in [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] train also stops here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 53rd Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 53rd Street started on March 15, 1913, and was completed in 1915. The station opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation between 1968 and 1970. The station was renovated again in 2017.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:53rd St BMT train.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The station before renovation]]\n\n===Construction and opening===\nThe 53rd Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> In 1912, during the Dual System negotiations, the construction of an extension of the Fourth Avenue subway from 43rd Street to 89th Street, just south of the [[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street station]], was recommended. The proposal was approved by the Board of Estimate on February 15, 1912. The PSC directed its chief engineer to create plans on June 14, 1912. The two contracts for the extension, Route 11B, were awarded on September 16, 1912, to Degnon Construction Company for a combined $3.8 million (equivalent to ${{inflation|fmt=c|index=US|value=3.8|start_year=1912|r=1}} million in {{inflation/year|index=US}}).<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nConstruction on Route 11B1, the section of the extension between 43rd Street and 61st Street, which includes the 53rd Street station, began on March 15, 1913. Originally, this section was planned to have two tracks, but after the connection to the [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach Line]] was added to the plan during the middle of construction, the plan was changed to four tracks. This section was completed in 1915.<ref name=\":12\" /> The 53rd Street station opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening\">{{cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 53rd Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|495|feet|meters|abbr=}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}) ({{Inflation|US|633000|1925|fmt=eq|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}) ({{Inflation|US|345021|1926|fmt=eq|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1960s ====\n[[File:53rd St BMT mosaic.jpg|thumb|225x225px|A former station name mosaic|alt=|left]]\nIn the 1960s, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 53rd Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions ({{Inflation|US|6585|1967|fmt=eq|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[45th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45th Street]] station and [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street station|Bay Ridge\u201495th Street]], including this station, on May 3, 1968.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHBIAQAAIAAJ&q=|title=Engineering News-record|date=1968|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref><!-- The information on the contract bid is likely in the 1968 Volume of Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation, but this has not been digitized.-->\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}} to the south,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Columns\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 ====\nAs part of the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]'s 2015-2019 Capital Program, the station, along with thirty other New York City Subway stations, were scheduled to undergo a complete overhaul as part of the [[Enhanced Station Initiative]]. Updates were to include cellular service, Wi-Fi, USB charging stations, interactive service advisories and maps, improved signage, and improved station lighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/01/08/subway_facelift_shutdown.php|title=MTA Will Completely Close 30 Subway Stations For Months-Long \"Revamp\"|publisher=Gothamist|accessdate=July 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801200338/http://gothamist.com/2016/01/08/subway_facelift_shutdown.php|archivedate=August 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/sites/governor.ny.gov/files/atoms/files/MTAStations.pdf|title=MTAStations|last=|first=|date=|website=governor.ny.gov|publisher=Government of the State of New York|access-date=July 18, 2016}}</ref> From January to May 2016, [[Grimshaw Architects]] worked on a design for the station's renovation, with [[Arup Group]] acting as a consultant.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe award for Package 1 of the renovations, which covered renovations at the [[Prospect Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Prospect Avenue]], 53rd Street, and [[Bay Ridge Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge Avenue]] stations on the BMT Fourth Avenue Line, was awarded on November 30, 2016.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/161114_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|last=|first=|date=November 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Citnalta-Forte Joint Venture was selected to renovate the three stations under a $72&nbsp;million [[design\u2013build]] contract, the first such contract in the subway system's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/news-nyct-subways/2017/03/22/three-brooklyn-r-stations-are-first-major-subway-station-modernization|title=Three Brooklyn R Stations are First in Major Subway Station Modernization Project|last=|first=|date=March 22, 2017|website=|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref> The station was closed on March 27, 2017, for these renovations,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/40/3/br-no-shuttle-buses-at-_bay-ridge-avenue-2017-01-20-bk.html|title=Shuttle scuttle: Riders demand extra buses during three subway stations\u2019 closure|last=Spivack|first=Caroline|date=January 16, 2017|work=|access-date=January 27, 2017|language=en|via=|newspaper=Brooklyn Paper}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/2017/3/22/15028712/mta-subway-station-closures-renovations|title=MTA will close these Brooklyn subway stops to facilitate upgrades|date=March 22, 2017|website=Curbed NY|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/planned_servChanges_NRtrains_mar2017.htm|title=Trains skip 53 St in both directions|date=March 26, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326183413/http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/planned_servChanges_NRtrains_mar2017.htm|archive-date=March 26, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> and reopened on September 8, 2017,<ref name=\"Sunset\">{{Cite web|url=http://brooklynreporter.com/story/sunset-parks-renovated-53rd-street-station-open-business/|title=Sunset Park\u2019s renovated 53rd Street station is open for business|last=DeJesus|first=Jaime|date=September 8, 2017|website=Brooklyn Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref> ahead of schedule.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://pix11.com/2017/09/08/newly-renovated-r-train-subway-station-transforms-into-commuter-dream-with-usb-ports-countdown-clocks/|title=Newly renovated R train subway station transforms into commuter dream with USB ports, countdown clocks|date=2017-09-09|website=New York's PIX11 / WPIX-TV|access-date=2017-09-10}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=45th Street\n|l1=45 St \n|2=59th Street\n|l2=59 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout BMT Fourth Avenue Line|prev2=45th Street|next2=59th Street}}\n[[File:Image of sign pointing to 95th Street at 53rd Street.jpg|thumb|An original mosaic, directing passengers toward the 95th Street-bound platform, is located above modern signage.]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref> The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the N stops here during late nights, but uses the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref>\n\nColumns run along the entire length of both platforms and are painted black.<ref name=\"Columns\">{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r24.jpg|title=A final view down the Bay Ridge-bound side platform with its narrow columns at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> Every other column has a \"53 Street\" sign on it in black with white text.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r22.jpg|title=A staircase up to the small mezzanine area and fare control form the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> All are rounded except for the ones near the two staircases to the station's main entrance, which was where the platforms were extended in 1970.<ref name=\"Columns\" />\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since that renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain yellow-painted cinderblock tiles. The yellow cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and black text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r2.jpg|title=A 53 Street platform sign, text and a arrow for 52 St is painted beneath this one.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r3.jpg|title=A 53 Street platform sign, text and a arrow for 52 St is painted beneath this one.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> During the 2017 renovation, the cinderblock tiles were refurbished and colored white with small recesses containing black tiles. [[ADA-accessible|ADA-compliant]] platform treads and a granite tiled floor, as well as indirect lighting atop the station wall, which was relocated from above the platform edge, were installed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/enhanced-53rd-street-r-subway-station-opens-sunset-park|title=Enhanced 53rd Street R Subway Station Opens in Sunset Park|last=|first=|date=September 8, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|website=Flickr.com|title=Reopening of 53rd St ESI Station|date=2017-09-08|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/mtaphotos/36710339210/|volume=|pages=|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|website=Flickr.com|last=|first=|title=53 Street Station Before Renewal|date=2016-09-02|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/mtaphotos/36712590600/|volume=|pages=|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe 2017 artwork at this station consists of nature-inspired mosaics by Brooklyn-based artist [[Mickalene Thomas]].<ref name=\"Sunset\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThe station's main entrance has two staircases to each platform and one to each northern corner of Fourth Avenue and 53rd Street. The [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] allows transfer between directions and contains some original mosaic directional and arrow signs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r19.jpg|title=Looking back towards the entrance turnstiles on the mezzanine level at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref> The one by the staircases to the southbound platform displays \"Ft. Hamilton &amp; Coney Island\" while the one by the Manhattan-bound platform staircases displays \"Down Town Trains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r18.jpg|title=A unique mosaic says Ft. Hamilton & Coney Island and points towards the platform To 95 Street at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r16.jpg|title=The passageway that leads to the two staircases down to the Down Town Trains platform at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe southbound platform has an additional entrance near the north end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r5.jpg|title=Another view approaching the High Exit Gate that leads to 52 St.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> Two platform-level [[turnstile]]s lead to a small landing before a three-flight staircase goes up to 52nd Street and Fourth Avenue. Prior to the 2017 renovation, the entrance was exit-only.<ref name=maps/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r11.jpg|title=A M subway entrance column with red on it on 4th Avenue, and the No Entry staircase down to the exit from 52 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> The landing area contained the original 1915 trim band with a single \"53\" tiled on it prior to the renovation of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r6.jpg|title=The only 53 tiling in the single band of trim that is still visible after passing through the High Exit gate that leads out to 52 St.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{Multiple image\n|align=center\n|direction=horizontal\n|image1=53rd St BMT entrance.jpg\n|width1=220\n|caption1=The entrance at 4th Avenue and 53rd Street before renovation, seen during a snowy day. This entrance is located next to a bus stop.\n|image2=53 Street entrance vc.jpg\n|width2=123\n|caption2=Modernized station entrance\n|image3=Reopening of 53rd St ESI Station (37106526515).jpg\n|width3=207\n|caption3=Interactive neighborhood map at entrance, added during renovation\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|53rd Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n{{external media\n|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69xbrgPuOWw Enhanced Station Initiative: 53 St Station Grand Opening]\n}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:298|BMT 4th Avenue|53rd Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/index.php 53rd Street Pictures]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/uv?pb=!5s53%20Street%20Station!6m43!1m42!7m1!1s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-uXsJQ9Qtf8U%2FWb8Ax9MgXiI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2F3Gx-5Eb9C04W_Rg86ro6rj_BFwNGgu9TACLIBGAYYCw%2Fw520-h260-n-k-no%2F!22m39!2m2!1e3!2s-uXsJQ9Qtf8U%2FWb8Ax9MgXiI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2F3Gx-5Eb9C04W_Rg86ro6rj_BFwNGgu9TACLIBGAYYCw!3m35!1e3!2e2!3m2!1i4352!2i8704!4m28!1m3!1m2!1i136!2i272!1m3!1m2!1i272!2i544!1m3!1m2!1i544!2i1088!1m3!1m2!1i1088!2i2176!1m3!1m2!1i2176!2i4352!1m3!1m2!1i4352!2i8704!2m2!1i512!2i512!3e1!10s-uXsJQ9Qtf8U%2FWb8Ax9MgXiI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2F3Gx-5Eb9C04W_Rg86ro6rj_BFwNGgu9TACLIBGAYYCw!9b1&hl=en-US Rebuilt Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/uv?pb=!5s53%20Street%20Station!6m43!1m42!7m1!1s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-louVPVixLTw%2FWb8A0auDXhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FOnWMyXAg7v4xbk1o1dtjeFTJC08T8BVCACLIBGAYYCw%2Fw520-h260-n-k-no%2F!22m39!2m2!1e3!2s-louVPVixLTw%2FWb8A0auDXhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FOnWMyXAg7v4xbk1o1dtjeFTJC08T8BVCACLIBGAYYCw!3m35!1e3!2e2!3m2!1i4352!2i8704!4m28!1m3!1m2!1i136!2i272!1m3!1m2!1i272!2i544!1m3!1m2!1i544!2i1088!1m3!1m2!1i1088!2i2176!1m3!1m2!1i2176!2i4352!1m3!1m2!1i4352!2i8704!2m2!1i512!2i512!3e1!10s-louVPVixLTw%2FWb8A0auDXhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FOnWMyXAg7v4xbk1o1dtjeFTJC08T8BVCACLIBGAYYCw!9b1&hl=en-US Rebuilt Mezzanine from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/uv?pb=!5s53%20Street%20Station!6m43!1m42!7m1!1s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-yZPQLAvs6k8%2FWb8A31fzxhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FI_tNYSz9mEULDCv3QgBdsc3WJU7x86OjACLIBGAYYCw%2Fw520-h260-n-k-no%2F!22m39!2m2!1e3!2s-yZPQLAvs6k8%2FWb8A31fzxhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FI_tNYSz9mEULDCv3QgBdsc3WJU7x86OjACLIBGAYYCw!3m35!1e3!2e2!3m2!1i4352!2i8704!4m28!1m3!1m2!1i136!2i272!1m3!1m2!1i272!2i544!1m3!1m2!1i544!2i1088!1m3!1m2!1i1088!2i2176!1m3!1m2!1i2176!2i4352!1m3!1m2!1i4352!2i8704!2m2!1i512!2i512!3e1!10s-yZPQLAvs6k8%2FWb8A31fzxhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FI_tNYSz9mEULDCv3QgBdsc3WJU7x86OjACLIBGAYYCw!9b1&hl=en-US Rebuilt 53rd Street Entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|lr=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|4ave=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:53rd Street (Bmt Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:BMT Fourth Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in the United States opened in 1915]]\n[[Category:1915 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sunset Park, Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the demolished station serving the IRT Third Avenue Line in Manhattan|53rd Street (IRT Third Avenue Line)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Brooklyn}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = 53 Street \n| font_color = black\n| font_color_2 = black\n| bg_color = #FFC800\n| image = Reopening of 53rd St ESI Station (36965174321).jpg\n| image_caption = Northbound R train arriving at the platform\n| address = 53rd Street &amp; [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]]<br>Brooklyn, NY 11220\n| borough = [[Brooklyn]]\n| locale = [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn|Sunset Park]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|38|37|N|74|0|55.86|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = BMT\n| line = [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]]\n| service = Fourth south local\n| service_header = Fourth south local header\n| connection = {{Bus icon}} '''[[New York City Transit buses|New York City Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|B11}}; {{NYC bus link|B37}} <small>(on [[Third Avenue (Brooklyn)|Third Avenue]])</small>; {{NYC bus link|B63}} <small>(on Fifth Avenue)</small><ref>{{cite NYC bus map|B}}</ref>\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4 (2 in regular service)\n| structure = Underground\n| wifi = yes\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1915|June|22|p=y}}<ref name=\"Station Opening\" />\n| close_date = {{start date and age|2017|3|27}} (reconstruction)\n| rebuilt = {{start date and age|2017|09|08}}\n| other_exits = Fourth Avenue and 53rd Street, Fourth Avenue and 52nd Street (southbound only)\n| code = 034\n| passengers = 2,378,056<ref name=\"riderref\">{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = 100.2\n| rank = 196<ref name=\"riderref\"/>\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=45th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=59th Street | line=BMT Fourth Avenue Line | service=Fourth south local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|allexceptnights}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n}}\n\n'''53rd Street''' is a local [[metro station|station]] on the [[BMT Fourth Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Located at 53rd Street and [[Fourth Avenue (Brooklyn)|Fourth Avenue]] in [[Sunset Park, Brooklyn]], it is served by the [[R (New York City Subway service)|R]] train at all times. The [[N (New York City Subway service)|N]] train also stops here during late nights, and some rush-hour [[W (New York City Subway service)|W]] trains stop here in the peak direction.\n\nThe 53rd Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, which was approved in 1905. Construction on the segment of the line that includes 53rd Street started on March 15, 1913, and was completed in 1915. The station opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the BMT Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]]. The platforms were lengthened in 1925 and again during a renovation between 1968 and 1970. The station was renovated again in 2017.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:53rd St BMT train.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The station before renovation]]\n\n===Construction and opening===\nThe 53rd Street station was constructed as part of the Fourth Avenue Line, the plan for which was initially adopted on June 1, 1905.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Rogoff|first=David|date=May 1961|title=The Fourth Ave. Subway|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0BzKvSWhrQBW4d3pvOGZaSERiZEhpQ24xT19DTktkQUVlLW5j/view|journal=New York Division Bulletin|publisher=Electric Railroaders' Association|volume=|pages=2\u201310|access-date=May 8, 2017|via=}}</ref> The Rapid Transit Commission was succeeded on July 1, 1907, by the [[New York Public Service Commission|New York State Public Service Commission]] (PSC), which approved the plan for the line in late 1907.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/?id=XoxBAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&dq=4th+Avenue+line#v=onepage&q=4th%20Avenue%20line&f=false|page=18|title=Fourth Avenue Subway, Brooklyn's New Transportation Line: A Part of the Dual System of Rapid Transit of the City of New York|date=June 19, 1915|publisher=Public Service Commission|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48901678/|title=Fourth Avenue Subway Is Sent To A Committee|date=March 20, 1908|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|access-date=May 4, 2017|pages=1\u20132|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs part of negotiations between New York City, the [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company]] (BRT), and the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company]] for the expansion of the city's transit network, the line was leased to a subsidiary of the BRT. The agreement, known as Contract 4 of the [[Dual Contracts]], was signed on March 19, 1913.<ref name=\":10\" /> In 1912, during the Dual System negotiations, the construction of an extension of the Fourth Avenue subway from 43rd Street to 89th Street, just south of the [[86th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|86th Street station]], was recommended. The proposal was approved by the Board of Estimate on February 15, 1912. The PSC directed its chief engineer to create plans on June 14, 1912. The two contracts for the extension, Route 11B, were awarded on September 16, 1912, to Degnon Construction Company for a combined $3.8 million (equivalent to ${{inflation|fmt=c|index=US|value=3.8|start_year=1912|r=1}} million in {{inflation/year|index=US}}).<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nConstruction on Route 11B1, the section of the extension between 43rd Street and 61st Street, which includes the 53rd Street station, began on March 15, 1913. Originally, this section was planned to have two tracks, but after the connection to the [[BMT Sea Beach Line|Sea Beach Line]] was added to the plan during the middle of construction, the plan was changed to four tracks. This section was completed in 1915.<ref name=\":12\" /> The 53rd Street station opened on June 22, 1915, as part of the initial portion of the Fourth Avenue Line to [[59th Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|59th Street]].<ref name=\"Station Opening\">{{cite news|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48814840/|title=Through Tube to Coney, 48 Minutes: First Train on Fourth Avenue Route Beats West End Line Eleven Minutes|date=June 22, 1915|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Station renovations ===\n\n==== 1920s ====\nOn June 27, 1922, the New York State Transit Commission directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at 23 stations on the lines of the [[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation]] (BMT), the successor to the BRT, to accommodate eight-car trains. As part of the project, 53rd Street's platforms would have been lengthened from {{Convert|495|feet|meters|abbr=}} to {{Convert|530|feet|meters}}.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u5kT80_w6rYC&pg=PA1277&dq=%22union+street%22+%22530+feet%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjngqLU7dboAhVLTt8KHapMD8IQ6AEwCHoECAkQAg#v=onepage&q=%22union%20street%22%20%22530%20feet%22&f=false|title=Proceedings of the Transit Commission, State of New York Volume III From January 1 to December 31, 1923|date=1923|publisher=New York State Transit Commission|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=1277|language=en}}</ref> Progress on the extensions did not occur until February 16, 1925, when the [[New York City Board of Transportation]] (NYCBOT) directed its engineers to prepare plans to lengthen the platforms at this and eleven other stations along the Fourth Avenue Line. It estimated the project's cost to be $633,000 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=633000|start_year=1925|r=-3}}) ({{Inflation|US|633000|1925|fmt=eq|r=-3}}). The BMT had been ordered by the Transit Commission to lengthen these platforms since September 1923.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/02/17/archives/12-bm-t-stations-to-be-lengthehed-transportation-board-orders.html|title=12 B-M. T. Stations To Be Lengthened; Transportation Board Orders Engineers to Prepare Contracts for Brooklyn Work. Cost Put At $633,000 Letter to Commission Urges That Company Be Compelled to Buy New Cars.|date=February 17, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 4, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The NYCBOT received bids for the project on February 25, 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193500/the-brooklyn-citizen/|title=Board Receives Platform Bids For B.M.T. Lines. Six Companies Submit Prices for Extending Subway Stations|date=1926-02-26|work=The Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=5}}</ref> The contract was awarded to Corson Construction Company for $345,021 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=345021|start_year=1926|r=-3}}) ({{Inflation|US|345021|1926|fmt=eq|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48193684/the-standard-union/|title=Brooklyn Wins Big Improvement Fund|date=1926-03-18|work=Brooklyn Standard Union|access-date=2020-04-07|url-status=live|pages=20}}</ref>\n\n==== 1960s ====\n[[File:53rd St BMT mosaic.jpg|thumb|225x225px|A former station name mosaic|alt=|left]]\nIn the 1960s, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) started a project to lengthen station platforms on its lines in Southern Brooklyn to {{Convert|615|feet|meters|abbr=}} to accommodate 10-car trains.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=New York City Transit Authority Annual Report For The Year June 30, 1960|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=1960|isbn=|location=|pages=16\u201317}}</ref> On July 14, 1967, the NYCTA awarded a contract to conduct test borings at eleven stations on the Fourth Avenue Line, including 53rd Street, to W. M. Walsh Corporation for $6,585 ({{inflation|fmt=eq|index=US|value=6585|start_year=1967}}) in preparation of the construction of platform extensions ({{Inflation|US|6585|1967|fmt=eq|r=-3}}).<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=HJTVAAAAMAAJ&dq=%22Union+Street,+9th+Street,%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=borings+JULY|title=Minutes and Proceedings|date=1967|publisher=New York City Transit Authority|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=379\u2013380|language=en}}</ref> The NYCTA issued an invitation for bids on the project to extend the platforms at stations along the Fourth Avenue Line between [[45th Street station (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|45th Street]] station and [[Bay Ridge\u201395th Street station|Bay Ridge\u201495th Street]], including this station, on May 3, 1968.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHBIAQAAIAAJ&q=|title=Engineering News-record|date=1968|publisher=McGraw-Hill|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref><!-- The information on the contract bid is likely in the 1968 Volume of Proceedings of the New York City Transit Authority Relating to Matters Other Than Operation, but this has not been digitized.-->\n\nAs part of the renovation project, the station's platforms were extended {{Convert|85|feet|meters|abbr=}} to the south,<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Columns\" /> and the station's elaborate mosaic tile walls were covered over with {{convert|8|by|16|in|cm|adj=on}} white cinderblock tiles. The latter change, which was also made to 15 other stations on the [[BMT Broadway Line|BMT Broadway]] and Fourth Avenue Line, was criticized for being dehumanizing. The NYCTA spokesman stated that the old tiles were in poor condition and that the change was made to improve the appearance of stations and provide uniformity. Furthermore, it did not consider the old mosaics to have \"any great artistic merit\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Burks|first=Edward C.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/21/archives/subways-colored-tile-gets-cover-up-job.html|title=Subways' Colored Tile Gets Cover\u2010Up Job|date=1970-02-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== 2017 ====\nAs part of the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]'s 2015-2019 Capital Program, the station, along with thirty other New York City Subway stations, were scheduled to undergo a complete overhaul as part of the [[Enhanced Station Initiative]]. Updates were to include cellular service, Wi-Fi, USB charging stations, interactive service advisories and maps, improved signage, and improved station lighting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2016/01/08/subway_facelift_shutdown.php|title=MTA Will Completely Close 30 Subway Stations For Months-Long \"Revamp\"|publisher=Gothamist|accessdate=July 18, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160801200338/http://gothamist.com/2016/01/08/subway_facelift_shutdown.php|archivedate=August 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.governor.ny.gov/sites/governor.ny.gov/files/atoms/files/MTAStations.pdf|title=MTAStations|last=|first=|date=|website=governor.ny.gov|publisher=Government of the State of New York|access-date=July 18, 2016}}</ref> From January to May 2016, [[Grimshaw Architects]] worked on a design for the station's renovation, with [[Arup Group]] acting as a consultant.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThe award for Package 1 of the renovations, which covered renovations at the [[Prospect Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Prospect Avenue]], 53rd Street, and [[Bay Ridge Avenue (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)|Bay Ridge Avenue]] stations on the BMT Fourth Avenue Line, was awarded on November 30, 2016.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/mta/news/books/pdf/161114_1345_CPOC.pdf|title=Capital Program Oversight Committee Meeting|last=|first=|date=November 2016|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Citnalta-Forte Joint Venture was selected to renovate the three stations under a $72&nbsp;million [[design\u2013build]] contract, the first such contract in the subway system's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/news-nyct-subways/2017/03/22/three-brooklyn-r-stations-are-first-major-subway-station-modernization|title=Three Brooklyn R Stations are First in Major Subway Station Modernization Project|last=|first=|date=March 22, 2017|website=|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref> The station was closed on March 27, 2017, for these renovations,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/40/3/br-no-shuttle-buses-at-_bay-ridge-avenue-2017-01-20-bk.html|title=Shuttle scuttle: Riders demand extra buses during three subway stations\u2019 closure|last=Spivack|first=Caroline|date=January 16, 2017|work=|access-date=January 27, 2017|language=en|via=|newspaper=Brooklyn Paper}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ny.curbed.com/2017/3/22/15028712/mta-subway-station-closures-renovations|title=MTA will close these Brooklyn subway stops to facilitate upgrades|date=March 22, 2017|website=Curbed NY|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/planned_servChanges_NRtrains_mar2017.htm|title=Trains skip 53 St in both directions|date=March 26, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326183413/http://web.mta.info/nyct/service/planned_servChanges_NRtrains_mar2017.htm|archive-date=March 26, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> and reopened on September 8, 2017,<ref name=\"Sunset\">{{Cite web|url=http://brooklynreporter.com/story/sunset-parks-renovated-53rd-street-station-open-business/|title=Sunset Park\u2019s renovated 53rd Street station is open for business|last=DeJesus|first=Jaime|date=September 8, 2017|website=Brooklyn Reporter|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref> ahead of schedule.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://pix11.com/2017/09/08/newly-renovated-r-train-subway-station-transforms-into-commuter-dream-with-usb-ports-countdown-clocks/|title=Newly renovated R train subway station transforms into commuter dream with USB ports, countdown clocks|date=2017-09-09|website=New York's PIX11 / WPIX-TV|access-date=2017-09-10}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=45th Street\n|l1=45 St \n|2=59th Street\n|l2=59 St\n|code=BMT Fourth Avenue Line\n|color=yellow\n|textcolor=black\n|deg=315\n}}}}\n{{NYCS Platform Layout BMT Fourth Avenue Line|prev2=45th Street|next2=59th Street}}\n[[File:95th St BMT Fort Hamilton.jpg|thumb|An original mosaic, directing passengers toward the 95th Street-bound platform, is located above modern signage.]]\nThis underground station has four tracks and two [[side platform]]s.<ref name=\"tracks\">{{NYCS const|trackref|trackbook3}}</ref> The R stops here at all times;<ref name=\"ttr\">{{NYCS const|timetable|r}}</ref> some rush-hour W trains stop here in the peak direction;<ref name=\"ttw\">{{NYCS const|timetable|w}}</ref> and the N stops here during late nights, but uses the center express tracks to bypass the station during daytime hours.<ref name=\"ttn\">{{NYCS const|timetable|n}}</ref>\n\nColumns run along the entire length of both platforms and are painted black.<ref name=\"Columns\">{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r24.jpg|title=A final view down the Bay Ridge-bound side platform with its narrow columns at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> Every other column has a \"53 Street\" sign on it in black with white text.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r22.jpg|title=A staircase up to the small mezzanine area and fare control form the Bay Ridge-bound platform at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> All are rounded except for the ones near the two staircases to the station's main entrance, which was where the platforms were extended in 1970.<ref name=\"Columns\" />\n\nPrior to the station's 1970 renovation, it was finished all in white and marble tile, and it had its own color scheme to allow regular passengers to identify the station based only on the color of the marble trimmings.<ref name=\":10\" /> Since that renovation, the station walls have consisted of white cinderblock tiles, except for small recesses in the walls, which contain yellow-painted cinderblock tiles. The yellow cinderblock field contains the station-name signs and black text pointing to the exits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r2.jpg|title=A 53 Street platform sign, text and a arrow for 52 St is painted beneath this one.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r3.jpg|title=A 53 Street platform sign, text and a arrow for 52 St is painted beneath this one.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> During the 2017 renovation, the cinderblock tiles were refurbished and colored white with small recesses containing black tiles. [[ADA-accessible|ADA-compliant]] platform treads and a granite tiled floor, as well as indirect lighting atop the station wall, which was relocated from above the platform edge, were installed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/press-release/nyc-transit/enhanced-53rd-street-r-subway-station-opens-sunset-park|title=Enhanced 53rd Street R Subway Station Opens in Sunset Park|last=|first=|date=September 8, 2017|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|website=Flickr.com|title=Reopening of 53rd St ESI Station|date=2017-09-08|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/mtaphotos/36710339210/|volume=|pages=|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|website=Flickr.com|last=|first=|title=53 Street Station Before Renewal|date=2016-09-02|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/mtaphotos/36712590600/|volume=|pages=|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe 2017 artwork at this station consists of nature-inspired mosaics by Brooklyn-based artist [[Mickalene Thomas]].<ref name=\"Sunset\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThe station's main entrance has two staircases to each platform and one to each northern corner of Fourth Avenue and 53rd Street. The [[mezzanine (architecture)|mezzanine]] allows transfer between directions and contains some original mosaic directional and arrow signs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r19.jpg|title=Looking back towards the entrance turnstiles on the mezzanine level at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Sunset Park|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/bkn/B9-Sunset_Park_2015.pdf|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|accessdate=August 2, 2015|date=2015}}</ref> The one by the staircases to the southbound platform displays \"Ft. Hamilton &amp; Coney Island\" while the one by the Manhattan-bound platform staircases displays \"Down Town Trains.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r18.jpg|title=A unique mosaic says Ft. Hamilton & Coney Island and points towards the platform To 95 Street at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r16.jpg|title=The passageway that leads to the two staircases down to the Down Town Trains platform at 53 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe southbound platform has an additional entrance near the north end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r5.jpg|title=Another view approaching the High Exit Gate that leads to 52 St.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> Two platform-level [[turnstile]]s lead to a small landing before a three-flight staircase goes up to 52nd Street and Fourth Avenue. Prior to the 2017 renovation, the entrance was exit-only.<ref name=maps/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r11.jpg|title=A M subway entrance column with red on it on 4th Avenue, and the No Entry staircase down to the exit from 52 Street.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> The landing area contained the original 1915 trim band with a single \"53\" tiled on it prior to the renovation of the station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/53r6.jpg|title=The only 53 tiling in the single band of trim that is still visible after passing through the High Exit gate that leads out to 52 St.|last=Cox|first=Jeremiah|date=June 9, 2009|website=subwaynut.com|access-date=March 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{Multiple image\n|align=center\n|direction=horizontal\n|image1=53rd St BMT entrance.jpg\n|width1=220\n|caption1=The entrance at 4th Avenue and 53rd Street before renovation, seen during a snowy day. This entrance is located next to a bus stop.\n|image2=53 Street entrance vc.jpg\n|width2=123\n|caption2=Modernized station entrance\n|image3=Reopening of 53rd St ESI Station (37106526515).jpg\n|width3=207\n|caption3=Interactive neighborhood map at entrance, added during renovation\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|53rd Street (BMT Fourth Avenue Line)}}\n{{external media\n|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=69xbrgPuOWw Enhanced Station Initiative: 53 St Station Grand Opening]\n}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?216:298|BMT 4th Avenue|53rd Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20150113014240/http://www.stationreporter.net/rtrain.htm R Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/bmt/53r/index.php 53rd Street Pictures]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/uv?pb=!5s53%20Street%20Station!6m43!1m42!7m1!1s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-uXsJQ9Qtf8U%2FWb8Ax9MgXiI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2F3Gx-5Eb9C04W_Rg86ro6rj_BFwNGgu9TACLIBGAYYCw%2Fw520-h260-n-k-no%2F!22m39!2m2!1e3!2s-uXsJQ9Qtf8U%2FWb8Ax9MgXiI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2F3Gx-5Eb9C04W_Rg86ro6rj_BFwNGgu9TACLIBGAYYCw!3m35!1e3!2e2!3m2!1i4352!2i8704!4m28!1m3!1m2!1i136!2i272!1m3!1m2!1i272!2i544!1m3!1m2!1i544!2i1088!1m3!1m2!1i1088!2i2176!1m3!1m2!1i2176!2i4352!1m3!1m2!1i4352!2i8704!2m2!1i512!2i512!3e1!10s-uXsJQ9Qtf8U%2FWb8Ax9MgXiI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2F3Gx-5Eb9C04W_Rg86ro6rj_BFwNGgu9TACLIBGAYYCw!9b1&hl=en-US Rebuilt Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/uv?pb=!5s53%20Street%20Station!6m43!1m42!7m1!1s%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2F-louVPVixLTw%2FWb8A0auDXhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FOnWMyXAg7v4xbk1o1dtjeFTJC08T8BVCACLIBGAYYCw%2Fw520-h260-n-k-no%2F!22m39!2m2!1e3!2s-louVPVixLTw%2FWb8A0auDXhI%2FAAAAAAAAyzU%2FOnWMyXAg7v4xbk1o1dtjeFTJC08T8BVCACLIBGAYYCw!3m35!1e3!2e2